"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429107","Home Office","false","2015-12-01","<p>The Department does not hold this information in the format requested.</p><p>All Suspicious Activity Reports received are subject to an initial assessment by the UK Financial Investigation Unit (UKFIU) in the National Crime Agency. The UKFIU Terrorist Finance Team identifies and acts upon SAR information relating to the detection and investigation of terrorist finance, whether submitted under the Terrorism Act (TACT) or the Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA).</p><p>Over the reporting period, the National Crime Agency received 1216 Suspicious Activity Reports under the provisions of the Terrorism Act 2000. These SARs were disseminated to the National Terrorist Financial Investigation Unit (NTFIU) and the Counter Terrorist Unit (CTU) network, to make an assessment of what further action was needed and in order for the information to be available in support of counter-terrorist investigations.</p><p>In many cases, a SAR will not merit a specific detailed investigation. However, the information remains searchable and may be used at any time to inform the development of intelligence and operational targeting.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429107/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-01T16:00:18.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429107/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429107/answer","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429107/answer/previousversion/31448","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-18","Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 29 October 2015 to Question 12956, how many of the suspicious activity reports received under the provisions of the Terrorism Act 2000 have been investigated; and how many prosecutions have resulted from those investigations.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","16923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429108","Home Office","false","2015-11-25","<p>The draft Bill requires the retention of additional data, known as internet connection records, by domestic CSPs who are under a data retention notice, to ensure that those responsible for law enforcement continue to have the powers they need to acquire communications data as technology develops and threats change.</p><p>The Government published an estimate of the additional cost of this provision of Â£174.2m over the 10 year period in the Communications Data Impact Assessment, alongside the draft Bill on 4 November.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429108/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T14:37:52.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429108/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429108/answer","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429108/answer/previousversion/31449","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-18","Communication Service Providers: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the cost of reimbursing communication service providers under the provisions of the draft Investigatory Powers Bill in the first 10 years in which an Act arising from that draft bill is in force.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","16912"
