ses</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>22</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>In the last five years, there has only been one case in which a former unaccompanied asylum seeking child had their claim for asylum certified and later lodged an out of country appeal against this decision. In this case the out of country appeal was dismissed.</p><p>The figures in the below table detail how many former unaccompanied asylum seeking children, whose claim for asylum was certified by the Home Office, have been removed from the United Kingdom in each of the last 5 years. The figure for 2015 is correct up to 30 June 2015.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Removals</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>No of Cases</strong></p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td colspan="3"><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td colspan="3"><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td colspan="2"><p><br></p></td><td colspan="3"><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td colspan="3"><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td colspan="3"><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>13</p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td colspan="3"><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>22</p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td colspan="3"><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="5"><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td><td><p><br></p></td></tr></tbody></table><br />","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429118/answer",,,,,"16863 ; 16864 ; 16865 ; 16866 ; 16867 ; 16869","2015-11-26T13:31:46.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429118/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429118/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-18","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many young people over 18 who claimed asylum as unaccompanied children and had their claims certified have appealed out of country in each of the last five years; and how many such appeals were successful.","false","Biography information for Sarah Champion","Rotherham","Sarah Champion","16868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429119","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-23","<p>There are no UK-specific estimates of the impact of international recruitment of health workers.</p><br /><p>The UK has signed the World Health Organisation Global Code of Practice on the International Recruitment of Health Personnel. Among its underlying principles is that developing nations who are experiencing shortages of healthcare staff should not be targeted for active recruitment. Adherence to the principles of the code is managed by the NHS Employers organisation.</p><br /> <br />","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429119/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T16:28:15.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429119/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429119/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-11-18","Developing Countries: Doctors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make an assessment of the effect of the recruitment of doctors to the NHS from developing countries on the health services in those countries.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","16770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429120","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-25","<p>The UK has so far provided around Â£4.5 million to partners working in Greece, many of which are active on Lesbos. This includes supporting the Red Cross for assistance and emergency first aid to refugees and migrants arriving on the beaches. We are also providing assistance to the IOM and UNHCR who are delivering essential coordination, reception and registration support, as well as direct physical assistance.</p><br /><p>It is right that the vast majority of our support goes to the region, our support is helping to build long term stability and resilience to help refugees build a life in neighbouring countries and prevent them falling prey to people smugglers and traffickers. For this reason, the UK has been at the forefront of the response to the crisis in Syria and the region. The UK has pledged over Â£1.1 billion to date, our largest ever humanitarian response to a single crisis. We are the second largest bilateral donor after the US and have done more than any other European country.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429120/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T14:53:06.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429120/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429120/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-11-18","Lesbos: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support is being provided to refugees currently on the island of Lesbos.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","16796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429121","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-25","<p>Our aid relationship with any government is based on an assessment of their commitment to our Partnership Principles, which include human rights. The Government of Pakistan has publicly recognised the problems facing minorities, and the need to bring an end to religious persecution. We remain fully committed to working in partnership with them to achieve this.</p><br /><p>We raise these issues regularly with the Government of Pakistan; most recently the Head of DFID Pakistan raised this issue in October as part of the annual Bilateral Assistance Talks. Withdrawing aid would undermine our ability to protect the poorest, including many minority and excluded groups.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429121/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T14:56:20.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429121/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429121/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-11-18","Pakistan: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make it her policy to attach conditions to aid to Pakistan relating to the prevention of persecution of and discrimination against Christians.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","16819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429122","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-23","<p>Expenditure by sector is reported in Statistics on International Development (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistics-on-international-development-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/statistics-on-international-development-2014</a>).</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429122/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T16:26:03.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429122/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429122/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-11-18","Developing Countries: Sanitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much of her Department's budget is spent on supporting water, sanitation and hygiene services; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","16873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429123","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-25","<p>Clean water and adequate sanitation in schools ensure safe and hygienic environments for learning. The UK Government supports the view that providing toilets at schools for girls is necessary to provide privacy and dignity. There is some evidence that WASH interventions in schools do improve attendance by girls but much evidence points to other important factors as well.</p><br /><p>In 2011, DFID published a systematic review of this issue. This determined that separate facilities for girls were likely to encourage their attendance at school, but insufficient alone to increase attendance and that there are many influential factors, including social and economic pressures on poor families. DFID therefore takes a holistic approach to this issue.</p><br /><p>The UK played a key role in ensuring that the recently agreed Sustainable Development Goals include a dedicated goal on water which aims to ensure universal access to water and sanitation by 2030.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429123/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T17:06:42.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429123/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429123/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-11-18","Developing Countries: Sanitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the relationship between clean water and sanitation in schools and girls' school attendance in developing countries; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","16874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429124","Department of Health","false","2015-11-24","<p>This information is not available centrally.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429124/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:40:00.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429124/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429124/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-18","Prisoners: Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will estimate the number of people in prison (a) as a result of and (b) with a gambling addiction.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","16878"
