"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429135","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-24","<p>The consultationâ is expected to be published in early 2016 and is likely to run for 12 weeks. It will be a public consultation and anyone will be able to respond. It is likely that the consultation will be brought to the attention of a number of specific groups, including motoring organisations, MOT industry groups, commercial vehicle trade associations and road safety organisations.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429135/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T15:21:27.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429135/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429135/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","Motor Vehicles: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Chancellor of the Exchequer's Financial Statement of 8 July 2015, Official Report, column 327, when the consultation on extending the deadline for new cars and motorbikes to have their first MOT test from three to four years will begin; who will be invited to respond to that consultation; and when that consultation will end.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","16881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429136","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-24","<p>The Quality Contract Scheme Boardâs report concerns a proposal under existing legislation. The intention is to introduce the Buses Bill later in this Parliamentary session, so proposals are still in development. We will of course consider the thoughts presented by the Quality Contract Scheme Board alongside a range of other perspectives.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429136/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T15:43:33.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429136/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429136/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","Bus Services: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer to Question 15214, what assessment his Department has made of reference in the Quality Contract Scheme Board's report to bus operators being compensated by the Government for future losses that might be incurred as a result of franchising.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","16886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429137","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-23","<p>The Secretary of State has not had any discussions with Transport for London (TfL) on the ability of its ticket machines to accept banknotes issued by Scottish banks.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429137/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T14:33:28.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429137/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429137/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","Transport for London: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with Transport for London on the ability of its ticket machines to accept banknotes issued by Scottish banks.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","16911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429138","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-23","<p>Along with Gatwick and Stansted, the Government sets night flight restrictions at Heathrow, using its powers under s.78 of the Civil Aviation Act 1982.</p><br /><p>These restrictions limit the number of flights between the hours of 23.30 and 06.00 that can take place during a particular season - there are two seasons per annum, winter and summer, which coincide with the use of Greenwich Mean Time and British Summer Time. Heathrow is limited to 5,800 flights a year during these hours, which translates in to an average of 16 flights per night. Due to a voluntary agreement which prevents scheduled movements before 04.30, most of these flights are from aircraft arriving between the hours of 04.30 and 06.00. It should be noted that these restrictions do not preclude additional aircraft from operating at Heathrow during the night period in the case of emergencies or severe disruption.</p><br /><p>As well as limiting the number of movements allowed within an airline season, these restrictions place requirements on the aircraft that can operate during the night period, and place seasonal limits on the amount of noise energy that can be emitted at Heathrow. Aircraft are certified by the International Civil Aviation Organisation (ICAO) according to the noise they produce and the higher the band an aircraft is certified as the higher quota amount it uses with each movement. The Government has also prohibited the noisiest types of aircraft from using the airport during the night. QC/4 aircraft are not allowed to be scheduled during the night quota period (2330 to 0600), and the highest rated QC/8 and QC/16 aircraft are prevented from operating at all during the entire night period (2300 to 0700).</p><br /><p>The Government will begin consulting next year on a new nights flight regime which will take effect from October 2017.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429138/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T16:36:32.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429138/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429138/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","Heathrow Airport: Night Flying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the number of night flights to and from Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","16936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429139","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-26","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold information on how many miles of local authority roads are in a poor structural condition in England or London.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429139/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T14:28:35.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429139/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429139/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","Roads: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many miles of local authority road are in a poor structural condition in (a) England outside London and (b) London.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","16782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429140","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-23","<p>The Governmentâs overall policy on aviation noise, as stated in the 2013 Aviation Policy Framework (APF), is âto limit and, where possible, reduce the number of people in the UK significantly affected by aircraft noiseâ. To achieve this, the Government believes in most cases it will be preferable to concentrate aircraft over as few routes as possible. The APF does however go on to say that âwhere there is intensive use of certain routes, and following engagement with local communities, it may be appropriate to explore options for respite which share noise between communities on an equitable basis, provided this does not lead to significant numbers of people newly affected by noise.â</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429140/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T16:46:01.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429140/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429140/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","Heathrow Airport: Air Routes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what his policy is on the concentration of flight paths over residential areas near Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","16861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429141","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-23","<p>In accordance with the Infrastructure Act, all reports published by the Office for Rail and Road in relation to their Highways Monitor function will be laid in the House before being released to the public. The first annual report will be laid in the House in summer 2016.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429141/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T15:24:27.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429141/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429141/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","Highways England: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to lay the Office for Road and Rail's first Highways England Monitor before the House when it is complete.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","16808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429142","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-23","<p>Air quality emission levels by mode are only compiled at a national level by the National Atmospheric Emissions Inventory. Its estimates are updated annually. Emissions from road vehicles are by far the greatest source of nitrous dioxide levels in Greater London.</p><br /><p>The main impact of aviation on ground local air quality relates to emissions during the landing and take-off phase up to about 3000 feet. Above this height the oxides of nitrogen and particulate matter which can cause respiratory problems get dispersed.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429142/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T14:15:49.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429142/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429142/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","Exhaust Emissions: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of aircraft on nitrous dioxide levels in Greater London.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","16860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429143","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-23","<p>With regards to part (a), (i) and (ii) of the question, the High Speed Rail headcount for permanent full time equivalents (FTEs) currently in post in the Department is shown in the attached table 1. The salaries shown are average DfT Central salaries. All staff are located in Great Minister House in London.</p><br /><p>With regards to part (b), (i), (ii) and (iii) of the question, the HS2 Ltd headcount for permanent full time equivalents (FTEs) currently in post is shown in the attached table 2. Table 2 also shows the split between staff based in London and in Birmingham, with salaries at each grade shown as averages.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429143/answer","016830 - Table 1 - DfT HS2 Related Salary Information.xlsx ; 016830 - Table 2 - HS2 Ltd Salary Information.xlsx","016830 - Table 1 - DfT HS2 Related Salary Information.xlsx ; 016830 - Table 2 - HS2 Ltd Salary Information.xlsx","Table 1 - DfT Staff ; Table 2 - HS2 Staff","Table 1 - DfT Staff ; Table 2 - HS2 Staff",,"2015-11-23T15:43:03.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429143/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429143/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people work on High Speed 2 in (a) his Department and (b) HS2 Ltd; and what the (i) grade, (ii) salary and (iii) location is of each such person.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","16830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429144","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-23","<p>I am not able to disclose the identities of companies who may have expressed interest in the HS2 Phase One Main Works Civils Contracts since that procurement process is ongoing at the present time and this information is commercially sensitive.</p><br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429144/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T14:38:01.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429144/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429144/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which companies have expressed an interest in bidding for the seven engineering contracts announced by the Chancellor of the Exchequer on his recent visit to China.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","16831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429145","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-23","<p>Since the start of the High Speed 2 project, High Speed Two (HS2) Limited and the Department for Transport have used two types of external legal advisers â solicitors (including parliamentary agents) and barristers.</p><br /><p>High Speed Two (HS2) Limited has appointed solicitors Eversheds LLP in relation to property &amp; planning and general commercial work, and Herbert Smith Freehills in relation to construction. High Speed Two (HS2) Limited has indicated to the Department that to date it has paid Â£2,202,410.59 to Eversheds LLP and Â£763,064.07 to Herbert Smith Freehills. Both figures exclude VAT.</p><br /><p>The Department has appointed a joint team of solicitors/parliamentary agents from Winckworth Sherwood and Eversheds LLP to provide support in relation to Phase One of the High Speed 2 project. To date, it has paid Â£4,019,170.18 to Winckworth Sherwood and Â£3,022,492.30 to Eversheds. These fees are correct up to the end of September 2015 and are exclusive of VAT.</p><br /><p>The Department has previously, or continues to, instruct the following barristers to support the HS2 Phase One hybrid Bill: Tim Mould QC, James Strachan QC, Lisa Busch, Richard Wald, John Jolliffe, Jacqueline Lean and Richard Turney. Each barrister is remunerated at government hourly rates agreed with the Attorney General. The current spend to date on these barristers in relation to the Bill is Â£1,404,978.96 and is exclusive of VAT.</p><br /><p>Since approximately 2010, the Department has also instructed a number of barristers on other HS2 work. These barristers will have been remunerated at government hourly rates agreed with the Attorney General, but unfortunately it would involve disproportionate cost for the Department to provide precise figures.</p><br /> <br />","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429145/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T16:51:17.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429145/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429145/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which legal advisers and barristers have been used by (a) HS2 Ltd and (b) his Department on matters relating to High Speed 2 since the start of the project; and how much each such adviser or barrister (i) has been paid and (ii) is owed.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","16832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429146","Wales Office","false","2015-11-23","<p>The Wales Office spend on (a) temporary staff, (b) consultants, (c) non-payroll staff, (d) administration and (e) marketing and advertising as a proportion of Wales Office expenditure in each year since 2010-11 is shown in the table attached.</p><p>The numbers shown are actual spend as published in the Wales Office Departmental Annual Report and Accounts.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429146/answer","UIN 16787.docx","UIN 16787.docx","UIN 16787: Table - Wales Office Expenditure","UIN 16787: Table - Wales Office Expenditure",,"2015-11-23T16:01:16.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429146/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429146/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-11-18","Wales Office: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how much his Department spent on (a) temporary agency staff, (b) consultants, (c) non-payroll staff, (d) administration and (e) marketing and advertising (i) in 2014-15 prices and (ii) as a proportion of his Department's expenditure in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","16787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429147","Wales Office","false","2015-11-23","<p>As recommended by the Treasury, Departments are encouraged to maintain a reserve. The Wales Office maintains a reserve of around 5% of its annual Departmental Expenditure Limit (DEL), which represents our forecast underspend. This underspend can increase or decrease if planned expenditure is higher or lower than expected. In 2015-16, our DEL is Â£4.432m which includes the Departmental reserve of Â£0.222m. Our forecast of Annually Managed Expenditure (AME) is Â£-0.020m.</p><br /> <br /><p>The reserve stated above was also our forecast underspend at the time of the summer budget in 2015. The Department does not forecast underspends for the following financial year at the March budget. Each March, the Wales Office focuses on completing the financial transactions and processes of that current financial year.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429147/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T13:17:02.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429147/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429147/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2015-11-18","Wales Office: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what estimate he has made of his Department's expected underspend against Departmental Expenditure Limits in 2015-16; what his Department's forecast is of total Annually Managed Expenditure in 2015-16; and what that forecast was at the time of the (a) Summer Budget 2015 and (b) March Budget 2015.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","16914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429148","Women and Equalities","false","2015-11-26","<p>Officials in my Department have liaised with the Department for Work and Pensions as the lead Department for the Family Test to embed it into the policy process. This has included training officials on applying the Test, disseminating relevant evidence, learning materials and best practice.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429148/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T17:52:12.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429148/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429148/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2015-11-18","Government Equalities Office: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what steps her Department has taken to embed the Family Test into its policy making.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","16801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429149","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-23","<p>JSA claimants do not have to declare a mental health condition, therefore the information requested is not available.</p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429149/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T15:12:17.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429149/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429149/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","Jobseeker's Allowance: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of claimants on jobseeker's allowance have registered as having a mental health condition.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","16844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429150","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-23","<p>JSA claimants do not have to declare a mental health condition, therefore the information requested is not available.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429150/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T14:33:16.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429150/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429150/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","Jobseeker's Allowance: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what monitoring his Department carries out on changes in the number of people on jobseeker's allowance registered as having a mental health condition; and what change there has been in such numbers since 2010.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","16845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429151","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-26","<p>Officials have undertaken a number of activities to embed the Family Test into the policy making process. This has included training officials on applying the Test, as well as disseminating relevant evidence, learning materials and best practice.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429151/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T09:52:37.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429151/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429151/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","Department for Work and Pensions: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department has taken to embed the Family Test into its policy making.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","16800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429152","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-23","<p>Jobcentre Plus delivers a flexible support model for claimants: a core regime of regular face-to-face meetings, flexible work coach support and a menu of support options. This includes a personalised service tailored to the individual needs of the claimant, such as Mental Health conditions, and the local labour market. Additionally, the Access to Work Mental Health Support Service offers support to individuals with a mental health condition who are absent from work or finding work difficult.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429152/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T15:41:37.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429152/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429152/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","Jobseeker's Allowance: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what support his Department makes available for people with mental health conditions who claim jobseeker's allowance in getting them back into the workplace.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","16846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429153","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-26","<p>DWP takes any suggestions of workplace bullying in any form very seriously.</p><br /><p>All employees are required to report instances of bullying and seek support through our internal HR Support teams. In the first instance they are directed to our dedicated HR Mediation and Investigation Service. These trained professionals are able to assist managers and employees in resolving workplace disputes including complaints of Harassment, Discrimination and Bullying.</p><br /><p>Immediate telephone support for individuals is available through our Employee Assistance Programme. Employees contacting the service because of bullying receive extra support and counselling. This service is accessible 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, 365 days a year.</p><br /><p>Where problems have been identified we have also been able to arrange specific Bullying and Harassment awareness sessions aimed directly at managers, with positive results.</p><br /><p>During this yearâs anti bullying week all employees were reminded of the support and guidance available.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429153/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T15:52:21.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429153/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429153/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","Employment: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to tackle workplace bullying.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","16820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429154","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-24","<p>DWP does not tolerate bullying in any form.</p><br /><p>Guidance on our approach to dealing with and managing bullying is available to all employees and managers, and our policy is that all cases of bullying should be reported.</p><br /><p>DWP capture absence data in a format that is standard across the Civil Service, which is by absence âtypeâ. Each absence may have a number of underlying causes, therefore it is not possible to estimate the number of days of work lost because of bullying. Nevertheless, DWPâs current Average Working Days Lost stands at 6.28 which is the lowest it has been in the last 12 months, and down substantially compared to 5 years ago when it stood at 8.2.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429154/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T12:47:29.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429154/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429154/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","Employment: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an estimate of the number of days of work lost because of bullying in the workplace in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","16821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429155","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-26","<p>The Department will study the report. However, as the authors make clear, their report does not show a causal link between the Incapacity Benefit reassessment process and rates of suicide, mental ill-health or use of anti-depressants.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429155/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T09:47:09.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429155/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429155/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the study entitled 'First, do no harm': are disability assessments associated with adverse trends in mental health? A longitudinal ecological study, published in November 2015 in the Journal of Epidemiology and Community Health.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","16822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429156","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-23","<p>This Department considers and responds to each request for information under the Freedom of Information Act, on its own merits. I can confirm that there have not been any changes to Departmental Policy in doing so.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429156/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T15:22:35.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429156/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429156/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","Department for Work and Pensions: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the reasons were for the recent changes in the proportion of resolvable  Freedom of Information requests whose answers were fully withheld.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","16829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429157","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-26","<p>Syrians entering the United Kingdom under the Vulnerable Persons Relocation scheme receive an initial 12 month support package, including accommodation, integration support and English language tuition. Local Authorities are actively engaged in this process. Those participating in the scheme will be able to work and will have access to some benefits (depending upon their individual circumstances and the eligibility criteria for those benefits).</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429157/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T16:48:52.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429157/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429157/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 2 November 2015 to Question 13828, what other benefits will be available to Syrian immigrants; and what assessment he has made of the effect the payment of such benefits will have on local authorities (a) in general and (b) with regards to the housing of Syrian migrants under the Vulnerable Persons Relocation Scheme.","false","Biography information for Mr Douglas Carswell","Clacton","Mr Douglas Carswell","16760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429158","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-23","<p>The day of the week on which claimants are asked to sign on is typically fixed during a claimantâs new jobseeker interview.<strong></strong>However, this may be varied because of the personal circumstances of the claimant or for operational reasons. This policy ensures that claimants are able to manage their lives and take advantage of work-related opportunities whilst remaining close to Jobcentre Plus support. Whatever signing day is agreed, be it linked to the NINO or otherwise, entitlement is not affected as this will still be tied to the date of claim.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429158/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T17:45:41.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429158/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429158/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","Jobseeker's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether it is his policy that the day of the week on which claimants are asked to sign on for jobseekers allowance should be varied.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","16774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429159","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-23","<p>The information requested is not available. However, the annual numbers and amounts of Winter Fuel Payments paid to all recipients in the EEA and Switzerland, by country, are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/winter-fuel-payments-by-eea-country" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/winter-fuel-payments-by-eea-country</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429159/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T11:54:03.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429159/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429159/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","Winter Fuel Payments: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department spent on winter fuel payments for UK citizens living in (a) Cyprus, (b) France, (c) Gibraltar, (d) Greece, (e) Malta, (f) Portugal and (g) Spain in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","16925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429160","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-23","<p>The current guidance for DLA decision makers on children with type 1 diabetes has been under review since March 2015. It is now near completion with conclusions reached in close collaboration with subject matter experts and will be published shortly.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429160/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T11:49:27.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429160/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429160/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","Disability Living Allowance: Diabetes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when his Department's review of guidance relating to the eligibility of children with Type 1 diabetes for Disability Living Allowance was initiated; and what conclusion that review reached.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","16926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429161","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-23","<p>Ministers discussed and considered transitional arrangements during the passage on the Pensions Bill 2011.</p><p>The Government carried out extensive analysis of the impacts of bringing forward the rise to age 66 when legislating for the change in State Pension age. A final Impact Assessment was published in November 2011 following Royal Assent the Pensions Act 2011.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/181461/pensions-bill-2011-summary-of-impacts.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/181461/pensions-bill-2011-summary-of-impacts.pdf</a></p><p>The Impact Assessment includes analysis of the decision to amend the timetable originally set out in the bill so as to cap the maximum increase at 18 months rather than 2 years. This concession benefited almost a quarter of a million women, who would otherwise have experienced delays of up to two years. A similar number of men also benefited from a reduced increase, and the concession was worth around Â£1 billion in total.</p><p>The Government will not be revisiting the State Pension age arrangements for women affected by the 2011 Act.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429161/answer",,,,,"16901","2015-11-23T15:51:17.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429161/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429161/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his oral contribution of 20 June 2011, Official Report, column 52, on state pensions for women, what meetings he has had on the transitional arrangements referred to (a) between 20 June 2011 and 7 May 2015 and (b) since 8 May 2015.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","16900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429162","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-23","<p>Ministers discussed and considered transitional arrangements during the passage on the Pensions Bill 2011.</p><p>The Government carried out extensive analysis of the impacts of bringing forward the rise to age 66 when legislating for the change in State Pension age. A final Impact Assessment was published in November 2011 following Royal Assent the Pensions Act 2011.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/181461/pensions-bill-2011-summary-of-impacts.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/181461/pensions-bill-2011-summary-of-impacts.pdf</a></p><p>The Impact Assessment includes analysis of the decision to amend the timetable originally set out in the bill so as to cap the maximum increase at 18 months rather than 2 years. This concession benefited almost a quarter of a million women, who would otherwise have experienced delays of up to two years. A similar number of men also benefited from a reduced increase, and the concession was worth around Â£1 billion in total.</p><p>The Government will not be revisiting the State Pension age arrangements for women affected by the 2011 Act.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429162/answer",,,,,"16900","2015-11-23T15:51:17.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429162/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429162/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-18","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his oral contribution of 20 June 2011, Official Report, column 52, on state pensions for women, whether he plans to make an announcement of transitional provisions prior to the introduction of the single-tier state pension.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","16901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429179","Department for Education","false","2015-11-30","<p>This Government has been giving consideration to the legal position on caste discrimination in light of the <em>Tirkey v Chandhok</em> Employment Appeal Tribunal judgment which suggests there is an existing legal remedy for claims of caste-associated discrimination under the âethnic originsâ element of Section 9 of the Equality Act 2010.</p><p>Our consideration of the research report commissioned by the coalition Government, designed to determine the feasibility of conducting a national survey to quantify the extent of caste discrimination in Britain, is part of this process.</p><p>We remain mindful of the Open Government Action Plan published by the Coalition Government in 2013, to the extent that this concerns the results of commissioned research.</p><br />",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429179/answer",,,,,"HL3664 ; HL3665","2015-11-30T17:18:34.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429179/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429179/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-18","Castes: Discrimination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the compatibility of their decision to delay the publication of their feasibility study regarding establishing baseline data to evaluate the effectiveness of caste legislation with their commitment to open government.","false","Biography information for Lord Avebury",,"Lord Avebury","HL3663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429180","Department for Education","false","2015-11-30","<p>This Government has been giving consideration to the legal position on caste discrimination in light of the <em>Tirkey v Chandhok</em> Employment Appeal Tribunal judgment which suggests there is an existing legal remedy for claims of caste-associated discrimination under the âethnic originsâ element of Section 9 of the Equality Act 2010.</p><p>Our consideration of the research report commissioned by the coalition Government, designed to determine the feasibility of conducting a national survey to quantify the extent of caste discrimination in Britain, is part of this process.</p><p>We remain mindful of the Open Government Action Plan published by the Coalition Government in 2013, to the extent that this concerns the results of commissioned research.</p><br />",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429180/answer",,,,,"HL3663 ; HL3665","2015-11-30T17:18:34.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429180/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429180/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-18","Castes: Discrimination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of whether it is now possible to establish baseline data that could be used to determine whether the law on caste discrimination is working effectively.","false","Biography information for Lord Avebury",,"Lord Avebury","HL3664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429181","Department for Education","false","2015-11-30","<p>This Government has been giving consideration to the legal position on caste discrimination in light of the <em>Tirkey v Chandhok</em> Employment Appeal Tribunal judgment which suggests there is an existing legal remedy for claims of caste-associated discrimination under the âethnic originsâ element of Section 9 of the Equality Act 2010.</p><p>Our consideration of the research report commissioned by the coalition Government, designed to determine the feasibility of conducting a national survey to quantify the extent of caste discrimination in Britain, is part of this process.</p><p>We remain mindful of the Open Government Action Plan published by the Coalition Government in 2013, to the extent that this concerns the results of commissioned research.</p><br />",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429181/answer",,,,,"HL3663 ; HL3664","2015-11-30T17:18:34.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429181/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429181/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-18","Castes: Discrimination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what further consideration they have given to whether amending the Equality Act 2010 to include the word "caste" would change or clarify the legal position, given the provisions already in place in section 9(5)(a) of that Act.","false","Biography information for Lord Avebury",,"Lord Avebury","HL3665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429182","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-01","<p>The Government set out its proposals for the cap on public sector exit payments in the consultation document published on 31 July 2015 and confirmed the design of the cap in the consultation response document published on 16 September 2015. The consultation document gave details of the number of exits over recent years that cost the taxpayer more than Â£100,000.</p><p>The precise number of those affected by the public sector exit payment cap will depend on the number and type of exits in coming years. However, in recent years the large majority of exits in the public sector are below the level of the cap. For example, the Whole of Government Accounts states that, in 2013-14, 1,838 out of 72,445 pay outs were in excess of Â£100,000.</p><br /><p>The exit payment clauses currently before the House of Lords in the Enterprise Bill set out how the cap is expected to apply.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429182/answer",,,,,"HL3667 ; HL3668 ; HL3669","2015-12-01T17:11:11.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429182/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429182/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-18","Public Sector: Redundancy Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is their estimate of how many public sector employees will be affected by the proposed Â£95,000 public sector exit cap.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL3666"
