"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429220","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-26","<p>Given the improved situation in Sierra Leone, the resumption of direct flights is currently being reviewed by the Government. Subject to the outcome of this review, we are prepared to process the appropriate permissions for flights to begin.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429220/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T14:31:29.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429220/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429220/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","Aviation: Sierra Leone","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether, following the World Health Organisation's designation of Sierra Leone as free from Ebola, they plan to support the resumption of direct flights from the UK to that country.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayman",,"Baroness Hayman","HL3704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429221","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-30","<p>The UK supports the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition military intervention in Yemen, which came at the request of legitimate President Hadi to the UN Security Council, the Gulf Co-operation Council, and the Arab League for support by âall means and measures to protect Yemen and deter Houthi aggressionâ. We are aware of reports, including from Human Rights Watch, of alleged violations of International Humanitarian Law by the Coalition. We have received repeated assurances from the Saudi Arabian-led coalition that they are complying with International Humanitarian Law and we continue to engage with them on those assurances. The Saudi Arabian authorities have their own internal procedures for investigations and we encourage them to be open and transparent in this. We have also raised our concerns with the Houthis on the importance of compliance with International Humanitarian Law and international human rights law.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429221/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-30T15:45:02.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429221/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429221/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answer by the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State, FCO, Tobias Ellwood MP on 20 July (HC6867), what assessment they have made of the legality of coalition airstrikes in Yemen, and to what extent that assessment differs from those produced by Human Rights Watch.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL3705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429222","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-02","<p>As set out in Table B.3 of their July 2015 Economic and Fiscal Outlook, the Office for Budgetary Responsibility estimate that, in 2016-17, the National Living Wage will leave receipts broadly unchanged. In 2017-18 and 2018-19, income tax and National Insurance Contributions (NICs) receipts are projected to stay constant but the overall impact of the policy on the public finances is forecast to reduce public sector net borrowing by Â£0.1bn. In 2019-0 and 2020-21, the policy is expected to increase income tax and NICs receipts by Â£0.1bn and reduce public sector net borrowing by Â£0.2bn.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429222/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T17:53:57.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429222/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429222/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-18","Living Wage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the additional anticipated receipts for HM Treasury as a result of the implementation of the National Living Wage in each year from 2016 to 2020.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL3706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429223","Department of Health","false","2015-12-02","<p>The Government has engaged with the care sector, including care providers, to understand the impact on the market arising from amongst other things, local authority commissioning behaviour and the introduction of the National Living Wage. This has included a number of deep dive sessions held with both care home businesses and providers of home care services.</p><br /><p>As part of its spending plans for the next four years the Government is giving local authorities access to Â£3.5 billion of new support for adult social care by 2019/20. Local authorities will be able to introduce a new Social Care Precept, allowing them to increase council tax by 2% above the existing threshold. The Government estimates this could raise nearly Â£2 billion a year for adult social care by 2019/20.</p><br /><p>Councils will need to increase the price they pay for care to cover costs for care providers such as the National Living Wage. To support this, the Social Care Precept puts money raising powers into the hands of local authorities which are best placed to target resources based on their understanding of their local care market.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429223/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T15:27:14.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429223/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429223/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-18","Social Services: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what consideration they have given to the viability of (1) the care home sector, and (2) the private home care provider sector, in the light of local government expenditure restraint and the implementation of the National Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL3707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429224","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>We work with regional and international partners, including all Gulf States, to tackle the threat posed by terrorist organisations, including by working to counter terrorist financing. We urge all international partners to implement UN Security Council Resolution (UNSCR) 2161 (on Al Qaida sanctions), UNSCR 2199 (on countering Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) finance) and UNSCR 1373 (on threats to international peace and security), and work to further combat the financing of ISIL through the Counter-ISIL Finance Working Group (Saudi Arabia is the Chair, Kuwait and Qatar are active members).</p><br /><p>The Financial Action Taskforce (FATF) is the global standard setter for anti-money laundering and counter terrorist financing. Qatar, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia are members of the Middle East and North Africa Financial Action Task Force (the regional grouping of FATF) which conducts mutual evaluations of its members to assess compliance with the international standard. A FATF report on terrorist financing published on 16 November 2015 noted that since 2010, Saudi Arabia had achieved the highest number of terrorist financing convictions out of the 33 jurisdictions who had achieved a conviction.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429224/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:18:39.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429224/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429224/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","Terrorism: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what action they have taken, and what action they plan to take, to put pressure on Qatar, Kuwait and Saudi Arabia to cut off financing for terrorist organisations.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL3708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429225","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-30","<p>We will continue to keep the travel advice for France under close review given the evolving security situation in France. We encourage anyone planning on travelling to France to subscribe to travel advice e-mail alerts.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429225/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-30T15:45:20.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429225/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429225/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","France: Terrorism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether they plan to make further changes to the FCO travel advice for France following the terrorist attacks in Paris on 13 November.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL3709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429226","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-30","<p>We continue to closely monitor the humanitarian impact of Russian airstrikes in Syria. We are particularly concerned at UN reports that Russian-backed regime offensives have caused the displacement of at least 140,000 people in Aleppo, Hama, and Idlib governorates since 5 October. We are currently not aware that the flow of refugees has increased as a result of Russian military action. However with displacement on such a scale we cannot rule out that it will have an impact on refugee flows.</p><p>Unlike the Assad regime and its allies, who are bombing indiscriminately, Coalition military efforts in both Iraq and Syria are specifically designed to minimise civilian casualties in line with International Humanitarian Law.</p><p>We continue to call upon all parties to the conflict to uphold International Humanitarian Law and protect civilians.</p>",,"Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429226/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-30T15:44:00.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429226/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429226/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-11-18","Syria: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of recent comments by European Council President Donald Tusk that Russian military action in Syria is increasing the number of refugees to Europe; and what assessment they have made of the impact of the US-led coalition's military action on the number of Syrian refugees.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL3710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429227","Department of Health","false","2015-12-01","<p>The findings of Antibiotic Research UK are consistent with the data included in the most recent report on English Surveillance Programme for Antimicrobial Utilisation and Resistance published on the 16 November 2015. In the winter of 2014 there was a 16.7% increase in antibiotic prescribing in general practice compared to the summer months.</p><br /><p>Public Health England is working to implement the UK 5 Year Antimicrobial Resistance Strategy and as part of this work our surveillance teams are monitoring the seasonality of antibiotic prescribing. It is unclear currently, whether the rise of prescribing in winter months is due solely to the increase in infections or whether some prescribing is inappropriate.</p><br /><p>In response to increased usage of antibiotics in winter months, public facing campaigns such as Stay Well This Winter, run by NHS England, take place to increase public awareness of inappropriate prescribing amongst other seasonal concerns.</p><p><strong></strong></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429227/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-01T13:20:19.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429227/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429227/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-18","Antibiotics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what conclusions they have drawn from the recent findings of Antibiotic Research UK about the possibility of a significant surge in winter antibiotic prescriptions; and what assessment they have made of whether government action is required.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL3711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429228","Home Office","false","2015-11-30","<p>The Home Office does not hold this information. However, the decision to release names and/or details of suspects in a criminal investigation are decisions for the police, which are guided in making such decisions by the College of Policing Authorised Professional Practice (APP) Guidance on âRelationships with the mediaâ.</p><p>A key principle of the guidance is that the police have a duty to safeguard the confidentiality and integrity of information (including personal data) which must be balanced against the duty to be open and transparent whenever possible.</p><p>There are clearly great risks in naming suspects and the guidance makes clear that decisions should only be made on a case-by-case basis, and that the police should not release the names of those who are arrested or suspected of a crime unless they have clearly identified circumstances to justify disclosure.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429228/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-30T12:14:36.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429228/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429228/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-18","Rights of Accused","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government how many persons interviewed by police, but not charged, have had their names released on the decision of a senior police officer because of the threat to life, detection of further crime, or because of public interest or confidence, in the last period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lord Morris of Aberavon",,"Lord Morris of Aberavon","HL3712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429229","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2015-12-02","<p>The House of Lords agreed to cease using vellum for public Acts in 1999, with a resolution to that effect being passed on 14 October 1999. At that time, the change was not agreed by the House of Commons.</p><p>Since then the House of Lords has continued to pay for the production of two copies of each public Act of Parliament, printed on vellum. (One copy is retained in the Parliamentary Archives; one copy is sent to the National Archives.) The Lords has done this even though it is not in accord with the October 1999 resolution of this House.</p><p>In the past six years (2009/10 to 2014/15) the Lords has spent a total of Â£620,440 on vellum Acts; an average of just over Â£103,000 per year.</p><p>This is despite the availability of archival paper which is of extremely high quality and durability. Private Acts of Parliament have been printed on archival quality paper since 1956, and I am not aware that vellum is now used for any other governmental or parliamentary records.</p><p>The National Archives have confirmed the view they took in 1999; that they do not require a vellum copy, and that archival quality paper is sufficient to maintain the public record.</p><p>Switching from vellum to high quality archival paper would, on a conservative estimate, save approximately 80% on current costs - or around Â£80,000 per year. The exact level of savings to public funds will depend on the number of Acts passed, and number of pages per Act, per year, and the precise specification and contractual arrangements agreed for future printing.</p><p>As well as being an expensive raw material, vellum requires a highly specialised form of printing which is not widely available, the machinery for which is expensive to maintain, and which is likely to be more difficult to procure on the expiry of the Houseâs current printing contract in March 2016.</p><p>As the start of a new Parliament seemed a natural point at which to implement the change previously agreed by this House, the main party Leaders, the Convenor and the Lord Speaker were consulted early in the present session, and the House Committee was informed in July 2015. I then wrote to the Chairman of the House of Commons Administration Committee on 17 September to invite that House to agree to the change.</p>",,"Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429229/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T17:55:35.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429229/answer","Biography information for Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429229/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2015-11-18","Public Acts","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees what consultation there has been about the proposals for record copies of public acts to be printed on paper rather than vellum.","false","Biography information for Lord Naseby",,"Lord Naseby","HL3713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429230","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-02","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not collect data in such a way that the average waiting time for responses to written communications can be calculated. The performance is measured as a percentage of post cleared within 15 and 40 working days of receipt. HMRC has published the information on the performance results including post turnaround in the Annual Report and Accounts 2014-15.</p><br /><p>HMRCâs data on response times for written communication cannot be easily analysed by customer group.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429230/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T17:46:54.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429230/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429230/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-18","Revenue and Customs: Correspondence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is the average time it takes HMRC to respond to written communications from (1) small businesses, and (2) personal taxpayers.","false","Biography information for Lord Oates",,"Lord Oates","HL3714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429231","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-02","<p>HM Revenue and Customs has a target to handle 80 per cent of call attempts to their contact centre helplines. It also aims to answer calls within 5 minutes.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429231/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T17:53:05.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429231/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429231/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-18","Government Departments: Telephone Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of what is an acceptable average period for (1) small businesses, and (2) personal taxpayers, to wait for their calls to a government department to be answered.","false","Biography information for Lord Oates",,"Lord Oates","HL3715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429232","Department of Health","false","2015-12-01","<p>We have put into legislation through the Health and Social Care Act 2012 that mental health should have equal priority to physical health. We have also committed NHS England through the NHS Mandate to achieve parity of esteem between mental and physical health.</p><br /><p>We are implementing the first waiting times targets for mental health services to ensure more people have timely access to care in the same way they do for treatment for physical health. We have also increased access to talking therapies through the Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme.</p><p><strong></strong></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429232/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-01T12:21:54.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429232/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429232/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-18","Mental Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what steps they plan to take to ensure equality of treatment for mental and physical illness.","false","Biography information for Lord Oates",,"Lord Oates","HL3716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429233","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-02","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) recognise that their customer service has not been good enough, and have taken major steps to improve, including recruiting 3,000 new staff into customer service roles, available outside normal office hours when many of their customers choose to call. This year has seen their biggest-ever training programme as HMRC build customer support teams that can move across a wide range of work according to customer demand. By the end of December 1,600 existing staff will be trained to cover a wider range of work. Hundreds of these people are already taking calls. These improvements have started to make a difference. Last month, HMRC answered more than 80 per cent of calls, and average queue times are now around 10 minutes or less.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429233/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T17:46:37.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429233/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429233/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-18","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what steps they are taking to reduce HMRCâs delays in answering telephone enquiries.","false","Biography information for Lord Oates",,"Lord Oates","HL3717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429234","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-02","<p>HM Revenue and Customs has not made such an assessment.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429234/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T17:51:07.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429234/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429234/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-18","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the cost to (1) small businesses, and (2) personal taxpayers, of HMRCâs delays in answering telephone enquiries in terms of lost productivity.","false","Biography information for Lord Oates",,"Lord Oates","HL3718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429235","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-30","<p>As the Strategic Defence and Security Review makes clear, Russiaâs illegal annexation of Crimea and destabilising activities in Ukraine directly challenge European security and the rules-based international order. We have long been clear that Russiaâs actions are unacceptable. Nevertheless we need to work with Russia on key areas of shared interest: in particular to end fighting in Syria, and to focus on the shared aim of destroying the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant. That was the basis on which the Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), met President Putin at the G20 Summit in Antalya on 16 November.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429235/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-30T15:48:00.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429235/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429235/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","National Security","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, following the recent atrocities committed by ISIL in France, Egypt and the Lebanon, whether they have reconsidered the statement by the Foreign Secretary on 10 March that Russia represented the "single greatest threat to UK Security".","false","Biography information for Lord Truscott",,"Lord Truscott","HL3719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429236","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-11-26","<p>The Government's position has been stated in the recently published Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 (Cm 9161). Russia's behaviour is hard to predict and although highly unlikely, we cannot rule out the possibility that Russia may feel tempted to act aggressively against NATO Allies. We also want to keep open the possibility of co-operation and will continue to seek to engage with Russia on global security issues, including international efforts to tackle the ISIL threat.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429236/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T17:01:43.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429236/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429236/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-18","Russia: Baltic States","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, following recent atrocities by ISIL against a number of countries, including Russia, they have reconsidered the statement by the Defence Secretary on 19 February that there is a "real and present danger" Russia could try to destabilise the Baltic states.","false","Biography information for Lord Truscott",,"Lord Truscott","HL3720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429237","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-30","<p>We have a shared interest with Russia in tackling ISIL and bringing peace and security to the region. We are concerned that the majority of Russian airstrikes in Syria to date have targeted areas in which ISIL is not present. It is important that Russia continues to engage in the International Syria Support Group.</p><p>At the G20, the Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), and President Putin agreed that the international community needed to find a way to work together to find a political solution to the conflict in Syria and focus on the shared aim of destroying ISIL.</p><br />",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429237/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-30T15:48:50.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429237/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429237/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","Russia: Islamic State","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what plans they have to co-operate with Russia in the fight against ISIL.","false","Biography information for Lord Truscott",,"Lord Truscott","HL3721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429238","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-02","<p>There are a wide variety of quasi-judicial decisions and each are subject to different statutory requirements. In many cases the reasons behind the decisions are published with the decisions, for instance where a Secretary of State decides to make, or not make, a Development Consent Order under the Planning Act 2008, the decision letter and associated order, if applicable, must be published.There are several reasons why decisions might not be published and those include national security, sensitive personal data or commercial sensitivity.</p><br />",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429238/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T17:35:09.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429238/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429238/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-18","Government Departments: Disclosure of Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of whether all quasi-judicial decisions made by government departments or agencies should be made public.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL3722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429239","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-11-27","<p>The Government believes in parity of esteem for all the people of Northern Ireland.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429239/answer",,,,,"HL3752","2015-11-27T14:31:58.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429239/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429239/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-11-18","Northern Ireland Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether members of the security forces are included within the concept of parity of esteem as required by the Belfast Agreement 1998.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL3723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429240","Cabinet Office","false","2015-12-03","<p>The information requested can only be provided at a disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429240/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-03T11:59:15.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429240/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429240/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-18","Cabinet Office: Disclosure of Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what non-disclosure agreements the Cabinet Office made in 2003â04, and on what date each agreement was made.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL3724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429241","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-02","<p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office no longer retains case files for employment tribunals for 2003 and 2004. However our records indicate we settled two 2 cases in each year. Settlement agreements at that time included a standard confidentiality or non-disclosure clause.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429241/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T15:29:18.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429241/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429241/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Disclosure of Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what non-disclosure agreements the FCO made in 2003â04, and on what date each agreement was made.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL3725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429242","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-11-26","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not hold a central record of non-disclosure agreements and the information requested could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429242/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T17:02:01.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429242/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429242/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-18","Ministry of Defence: Disclosure of Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what non-disclosure agreements the Ministry of Defence made in 2003â04, and on what date each agreement was made.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL3726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429243","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-08","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p><p>The Ministry of Justice is the successor department to the Department for Constitutional Affairs. Searches have been conducted for the information requested. These searches have revealed no trace of any records that relate to such non-disclosure agreements, nor any references to records that were held previously and destroyed.</p>",,"Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429243/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-08T15:32:35.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429243/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429243/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-11-18","Department for Constitutional Affairs: Disclosure of Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what non-disclosure agreements the Department for Constitutional Affairs made in 2003â04, and on what date each agreement was made.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL3727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429244","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-30","<p>According to the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs website, in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs) in 2013 there were 38 Palestinians fatalities and 3,800 injured; in 2014 there were 2,310 Palestinian fatalities and 16,626 injured; and so far from 1 January 2015 to 16 November 2015 there have been 106 Palestinian fatalities and 10,626 injured. According to the same website, there were 77 Israeli fatalities in 2014 in the OPTs; and so far from 1 January to 16 November 2015 there have been 14 Israeli fatalities in the OPTs.</p><p>We regularly discuss these issues with the Israeli government, both our condemnation of the attacks and the need to ensure justice for victims, and for the need for the perpetrators to be arrested and brought to justice. Officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv most recently discussed these issues with the Israeli Ministry of Justice on 3 November 2015.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429244/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-30T15:49:28.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429244/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429244/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what information they have received from the UN or other independent sources about the number of (1) deaths of, and (2) injuries to, (a) Palestinians, and (b) Israelis, in the Occupied Palestinian Territories as a result of attacks for each of the last three years; what information they have on the number of perpetrators brought to justice for such attacks in the last 12 months; and what representations they have made to the government of Israel in the past 12 months on those issues.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL3728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429245","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-02","<p>There has been numerous discussions between my officials and Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) on the franchise obligation to extend Oyster pay as you go and Contactless payment to Epsom. GTR is currently working with TfL closely to deliver this as soon as is practical and we are applying lessons learned from extending Oyster to Gatwick to extending Oyster to Epsom.</p><br />",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429245/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T15:19:18.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429245/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429245/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","Epsom Station","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what discussions they have had with Govia Thameslink Railway about whether it still intends to activate the Oyster card reader installed at Epsom station, and if so, when it intends to do so.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL3729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429246","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-02","<p>To help identify and disseminate good practice in implementing shared space, the Department for Transport is working with the Chartered Institution of Highways and Transportation, who are preparing updated guidance. This work aims to use the practical experience gained from recent shared space schemes to provide good practice advice to local authorities and other interested organisations. To help inform this work, as the Minister responsible for this issue, my Hon Friend, the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Transport, the Hon Member for Harrogate and Knaresborough, Andrew Jones, has written to all local authorities asking them to provide information on relevant schemes to the Department by the end of November.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429246/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T15:20:03.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429246/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429246/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","Shared Spaces","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government how they encourage local authorities and other interested organisations to share best practice regarding the introduction and operation of shared space for vehicles and pedestrians.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL3730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429247","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-30","<p>As this scheme is sponsored by the Welsh Government, we have made no such assessment.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429247/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-30T12:22:43.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429247/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429247/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-18","Shrewsbury-Chester Railway Line","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what assessment they have made of the causes of delays to work on doubling the rail line between Rossett Junction and Saltney Junction, and when they expect the work to be completed.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL3731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429379","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>I discussed central registers of beneficial ownership with the Premiers of the Cayman Islands, the British Virgin Islands and Bermuda on 23 November and will have a further opportunity to do so when they are in London next week for the Joint Ministerial Council.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429379/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T15:39:37.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429379/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/429379/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","British Overseas Territories: Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the governments of British Overseas Territories with financial centres on central registers of beneficial ownership.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","902319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431833","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) met his French counter-part Laurent Fabius in Vienna the day after the cowardly terrorist attacks and offered hiscondolences to the French people. The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the member for Witney (Mr Cameron) met President Hollande yesterday to discuss how we can strengthen the counter-terrorism co-operation between our two countries and work together to defeat ISIL.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431833/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T14:56:33.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431833/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431833/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","France: Terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his French counterpart on the ISIL attacks in Paris and the implications of those attacks for the Government's foreign policy.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","902323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431834","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>We have raised concerns with the Saudi Government on alleged breaches of international humanitarian law and have received repeated assurances of compliance. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) discussed this with the Saudi Arabian Foreign Minister during his visit to Riyadh on 28 October, and most recently in Vienna on 14 November.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431834/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T14:09:12.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431834/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431834/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he plans to take to ensure that potential breaches of international humanitarian law by the Saudi-led coalition in Yemen are investigated.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","902325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431835","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>Ministers discuss the current migration crisis with EU counterparts and those from other affected regions on a regular basis. Last night, The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) met with African and EU representatives as part of a British Chairmanship of the Khartoum Process.The UK is playing a leading role in taking forward joint efforts.</p><p>For example, countering people smuggling will be a priority for the UK in its engagement with a new Libyan Government resulting from the UN-led process.The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron)announced in Valletta Â£200 million of new UK money for projects in Africa to address the root causes of migration. 31 European nations and 36 African nations attended the Valletta Summit on Migration earlier this month.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431835/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T14:55:49.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431835/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431835/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in the EU, Africa and the Middle East on diplomatic steps to tackle the refugee crisis in the Mediterranean.","false","Biography information for Wendy Morton","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton","902321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431836","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>The Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron) has set out substantial reforms in four key areas to fix the problems in the UK's relationship with the EU. Technical talks have been ongoing since July. The Prime Minister updated leaders at the October European Council and wrote to President Tusk on 10 November. Leaders will return to the issue at the December European Council.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431836/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T14:54:41.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431836/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431836/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","EU Reform","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the progress of negotiations to reform the EU and the UK's relationship with the EU.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Harris","Castle Point","Rebecca Harris","902320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431837","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>Earlier this month, my Rt Hon Friend the Foreign Secretary chaired a UN Security Council meeting to rally international support on Somalia. This included adoption of the UK drafted resolution to strengthen the UNâs logistical support to AMISOM and the need for progress on an electoral process in 2016.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431837/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T14:06:37.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431837/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/431837/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-18","Somalia: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent diplomatic steps he has taken to promote peace in Somalia.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","902324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428629","Department for Education","false","2015-11-25","<p>The statutory responsibility for transport to education or training for 16- to 18-year-olds rests with local authorities who are expected to make appropriate decisions bearing in mind local circumstances. However, most young people have access to a discount or concession on local travel, from their local transport providers, their local authority, or from their education or training provider.</p><p>Young people are participating at their highest rate since consistent records began with 90.8% of 16- and 17-year-olds being in education and work based learning (apprenticeships) at the end of 2014.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428629/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T11:56:57.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428629/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428629/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-17","Unemployment: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the numbers of 16 to 24 year olds who have turned down training or further education for transport reasons in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","16578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428630","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-24","<p>The decision to withdraw the 2015/16 ESOL Plus (Mandation) funding was taken in the knowledge that providers could use their adult skills budget to continue to provide ESOL training for jobseekers and therefore mitigate any adverse impact. Our data showed that the numbers of claimants being referred to ESOL Plus (Mandation) provision was significantly lower than originally anticipated.</p><p>Adults who are granted refugee status or humanitarian protection become eligible for skills funding through the adult skills budget, as any other English resident and are not subject to the normal 3 year qualifying period.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428630/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T14:14:04.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428630/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428630/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-17","Refugees: English Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of withdrawal of ESOL Plus mandated funding on the ability of refugees in the UK to access ESOL courses.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","16584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428631","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-23","<p>The Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) recently published its policy framework for the student opportunity allocation: 'Delivering opportunities for students and maximising their success' which can be found at the following link: <a href="http://www.hefce.ac.uk/pubs/year/2015/201514/" target="_blank">http://www.hefce.ac.uk/pubs/year/2015/201514/</a>. This set out its expectation that new initiatives will only be funded where they have robust evaluation plans in place, including the application of suitable research methods and the appropriate use of individual and national level data. HEFCE also plans to develop a framework setting out the outcomes against which the HE sector will be expected to demonstrate the impact and effectiveness of its work. It is envisaged this will include a range of educational, labour market and, where possible, wider societal outcomes.</p><br />","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428631/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T14:25:22.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428631/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428631/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-17","Students: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department plans to measure the (a) educational, (b) labour market and (c) societal outcomes of student opportunity allocation funding using individual-based data on a national level.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","16612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428632","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-20","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer that I gave on 25 June 2015 in response to PQ 3380. The answer can be accessed using the following link:</p><br /><p>www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=QuestionsWithAnswersOnly&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;use-dates=True&amp;answered-from=2015-06-25&amp;answered-to=2015-06-26&amp;member=4107.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428632/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T12:47:42.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428632/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428632/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-17","Banks: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to prevent local high street bank branches from closing.","false","Biography information for Chris Davies","Brecon and Radnorshire","Chris Davies","16629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428634","Cabinet Office","false","2015-11-20","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428634/answer","16628 .pdf","16628 .pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Level of Employment","UKSA Letter to Member - Level of Employment",,"2015-11-20T10:46:06.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428634/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428634/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-17","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what progress the Government has made on increasing the level of employment in (a) North Lincolnshire, (b) East Yorkshire and (c) England since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","16628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428635","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-20","<p>It is not possible to quantify the exact effect of benefit duration on the likelihood of re-employment as information on the destinations of people leaving benefits is not recorded for all claimants.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428635/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T12:52:55.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428635/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428635/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-17","Long Term Unemployed People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment the Government has made of the effect on the likelihood of people's reemployment of their prior length of absence from work; and what steps the Government is taking to address that matter.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","16623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428636","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-24","<p>The Chancellor will set out the next steps in his plans for the Northern Powerhouse and investment in the environment in the combined Autumn Statement and Spending Review on 25 November.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428636/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T14:20:03.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428636/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428636/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-17","Environment Protection: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to encourage investment in improvement of the environment as part of the Northern Powerhouse initiative.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","16588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428637","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-20","<p>A new exemption from tax and National Insurance Contributions for councillorsâ travel expenses will take effect from 6 April 2016. This was legislated for in the Summer Finance Bill. It will apply to travel expenses paid to councillors across the UK, including those in Northern Ireland.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428637/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T12:48:53.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428637/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428637/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-17","Councillors: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on the taxation of travel expenses for councillors in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Sammy Wilson","East Antrim","Sammy Wilson","16597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428638","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-25","<p>The Government is committed to competition and diversity in financial services and would like to see firms with a range of business compete and succeed.</p><p>The Government has supported both the Peer-to-Peer (P2P) and Crowdfunding sectors, which provide alternative sources of finance for both businesses and individuals, by introducing a proportionate regulatory regime as well as other policies, such as the inclusion of P2P loans in ISAs.</p><p>The Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 contained two policies to support Small and Medium-sized Enterprises (SMEs) in accessing finance. The first requires the major banks share information on their SME customers with other lenders through designated Credit Reference Agencies. This will improve the ability of challenger banks and alternative finance providers to conduct accurate risk assessments and level the playing field between providers. The second requires major banks to refer SMEs they reject for finance, with the SMEs permission, to âfinance platformsâ that can match SMEs with alternative finance providers.</p><p>The Government has established the British Business Bank to support the development of diverse finance markets for smaller businesses in the UK. The British Business Bankâs Â£950m Business Finance Partnership aims to diversify the sources of finance available to smaller and mid-sized firms and reduce their dependence on bank finance. Â£863m has been allocated to funds supporting mid-sized firms, with Â£333m already invested alongside private money, generating over Â£1bn of lending to businesses.</p><p>The Government has also continued to support the building societies sector through a number of measures including: carving out building societies from the Independent Commission on Banking ring-fencing regulations, extending ISA eligibility to Core Capital Deferred Shares, and applying a Â£25m sector-specific allowance to carried-forward losses for Corporation Tax. More recently, the Government listened to the concerns of smaller organisations, including building societies, when taking steps to remove the reverse burden of proof from the senior managers regime.</p><p>The Government has also taken significant steps to support the credit union sector by investing Â£38m in the sector through the Department of Work and Pensionsâ (DWP) Credit Union Expansion Project, changing legislation to allow credit unions to admit corporate members, providing Â£500,000 to help armed forces personnel access credit union services and launching a Call for Evidence which allowed all credit unions, regardless of size or influence, the opportunity to contribute their vision for the future of the sector to the wider debate.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428638/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T12:23:41.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428638/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428638/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-17","Banks: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to support greater diversification in forms of lending in the UK banking sector.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","16624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428639","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-11-26","<p>The National Planning Policy Framework is clear that local planning authorities should work with other authorities and providers to assess the quality and capacity of infrastructure, and its ability to meet forecast demands.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428639/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T15:19:43.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428639/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428639/answer","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428639/answer/previousversion/31108","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-17","Utilities: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what statutory obligations are placed on local authorities to have an accurate assessment of the (a) capacity, (b) location and (c) other aspects of local utility infrastructure.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","16611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428640","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-11-24","<p>The Government recently published a discussion paper about parking on private land entitled âParking reform: tackling unfair practicesâ. The issue of companies charging for overstaying was raised in a significant number of responses. My Department is considering all of the circumstances surrounding overstay charges. We will publish a response to the discussion paper in due course setting out the Governmentâs proposed course of action.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428640/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T15:02:37.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428640/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428640/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-17","Parking: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment he has made of the legality of private car park companies charging for overstaying.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","16577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428641","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-11-23","<p>The Northern Powerhouse is about bringing together northern cities and regions to maximise the potential of the North and help drive UK economic growth.</p><p>We will do this by investing in science and technology, transport, digital and innovation, culture and tourism across the region, alongside devolving power to give the North a powerful new voice, investment and decision-making powers to meet these ambitions. Improving the environment could be a consideration in how we take forward these investments and activities.</p><p><br> <br></p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428641/answer",,,,,"16586","2015-11-23T16:54:33.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428641/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428641/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-17","Environmental Protection: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to improve the environment as part of the Northern Powerhouse initiative.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","16585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428642","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-11-23","<p>The Northern Powerhouse is about bringing together northern cities and regions to maximise the potential of the North and help drive UK economic growth.</p><p>We will do this by investing in science and technology, transport, digital and innovation, culture and tourism across the region, alongside devolving power to give the North a powerful new voice, investment and decision-making powers to meet these ambitions. Improving the environment could be a consideration in how we take forward these investments and activities.</p><p><br> <br></p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428642/answer",,,,,"16585","2015-11-23T16:54:33.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428642/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428642/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-17","Recreation Spaces: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to increase access to green space as part of the Northern Powerhouse initiative.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","16586"
