"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428647","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-25","<p>The Department for Culture, Media and Sport is responsible for the regulatory framework for the distribution of National Lottery good causes, which is currently 40% for good causes, 20% for arts, 20% for heritage and 20% for sports.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428647/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T15:23:31.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428647/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428647/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-17","Big Lottery Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether he plans to redirect proceeds from the National Lottery away from the Big Lottery Fund to fulfil his Department's existing commitments to fund the arts, heritage and sport.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","16544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428649","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-23","<p>In line with the armsâ length principle of lottery distribution, the Big Lottery Fund itself decides how much of its funding to allocate to Scotland and to each of the other home nations.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428649/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T13:31:05.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428649/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428649/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-17","Big Lottery Fund: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether his Department plans to reduce the Big Lottery Fund budget for Scotland.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","16638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428650","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-23","<p>The Big Lottery Fund decides how much of its funding to allocate to Scotland.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428650/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T13:29:38.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428650/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428650/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-17","Big Lottery Fund: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions his Department has had with the voluntary sector in Scotland on the level of funding for Scotland's Big Lottery Fund.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","16639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428651","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-25","<p>The Big Lottery Fund decides how much of its funding to allocate to each of the home nations. Scotland is allocated 11.5 per cent of the Big Lottery Funds proceeds from the National Lottery after administration costs, and 10 per cent of the Fundâs Lottery income is allocated to a UK portfolio, from which Scotland also benefits.</p><br />","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428651/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T15:20:31.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428651/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428651/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-17","Big Lottery Fund: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of national lottery sales income has been allocated to the Big Lottery Fund budget for Scotland in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","16630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428652","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-11-24","<p>Since the mid 1990s Reserves have had a variety of pension options to choose from when mobilised, including access to an Armed Forces pension scheme for the period of their mobilisation. However, there has been no special or additional pension provision made for part-time military personnel beyond the following statutory arrangements.</p><p>Since 1 April 2015 all members of the UK part-time Volunteer Reserves have been enrolled in the Armed Forces Pension Scheme 2015 and for the first time all their attendance-based paid service now counts as pensionable. Prior to that, from 6 April 2005 to 31 March 2015, personnel serving on an Additional Duties Commitment (ADC) were eligible to join the Reserve Forces Pension Scheme 2005 (RFPS 05). Those members of the RFPS 05 still serving on an ADC on 1 April 2015 transferred to the new scheme unless they met the criteria for transitional protection.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428652/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:41:50.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428652/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428652/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-17","Armed Forces: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, in what instances special or additional pension provision has been made for part-time military personnel in the last 20 years.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","16614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428653","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-11-20","<p>All Ministry of Defence (MOD) records held at Swadlincote that are subject to the Public Records Acts have been assessed for ongoing business or potential historical value. More than one third of the files at Swadlincote have been selected for transfer to The National Archives. These are largely military service records, which The National Archives has identified as being required for permanent preservation.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428653/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:17:12.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428653/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428653/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-17","Ministry of Defence: Public Records","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of the files held at Swadlincote that are subject to the Public Records Act 1958 have been (a) assessed by and (b) released to the National Archive.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","16554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428654","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-11-24","<p>Full time members of the Ulster Defence Regiment (UDR) had an automatic entitlement to become members of the Armed Forces Pension Scheme. Part-time members of the UDR were engaged under different terms to the full time regular members of the Regiment. These terms were similar to those of the Territorial Army and reflected that part-time engagements were often on an irregular, intermittent and short-term basis.Part-time membersof the UDR were not members of an Armed Forces Pension Scheme.</p><p>There are no plans to review the pension entitlement for former members of the Ulster Defence Regiment.</p><br />","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428654/answer",,,,,"16582","2015-11-24T16:40:13.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428654/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428654/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-17","Ulster Defence Regiment: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether a pension was provided to (a) full and (b) part-time members of the Ulster Defence Regiment who latterly served in the Home Battalions of the Royal Irish Regiment.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","16581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428655","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-11-24","<p>Full time members of the Ulster Defence Regiment (UDR) had an automatic entitlement to become members of the Armed Forces Pension Scheme. Part-time members of the UDR were engaged under different terms to the full time regular members of the Regiment. These terms were similar to those of the Territorial Army and reflected that part-time engagements were often on an irregular, intermittent and short-term basis.Part-time membersof the UDR were not members of an Armed Forces Pension Scheme.</p><p>There are no plans to review the pension entitlement for former members of the Ulster Defence Regiment.</p><br />","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428655/answer",,,,,"16581","2015-11-24T16:40:13.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428655/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428655/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-17","Ulster Defence Regiment: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department plans to provide a pension to part-time soldiers who served in the Ulster Defence Regiment.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","16582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428656","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-11-24","<p>I have considered this matter and will bring forward an amendment in the Armed Forces Bill to extend the remit of the Veterans Advisory and Pensions Committees.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428656/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:43:02.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428656/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428656/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-17","Veterans Advisory and Pensions Committees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 16 November 2015 to Question 15947, on the Veterans Advisory and Pensions Committees, how long he expects the matter to be under consideration.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","16565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428657","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-11-20","<p>The Historical Enquiries Team and the De Silva Review were able to access any Ministry of Defence file at Swadlincote or elsewhere which was relevant to their functions, but the Department does not record the number of files which were actually inspected or copied over time by members of these teams.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428657/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:17:55.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428657/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428657/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-17","Public Records: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many files held at Swadlincote his Department has made available to the (a) Historical Enquiries Team and (b) Da Silva Review.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","16556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428658","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-11-20","<p>The Ministry of Defence's (MOD) policy for the capture, management and final disposal, including transfer to The National Archives, of the MOD's records is detailed in Joint Service Publication 441-Defence Records Management Policy and Procedures. A copy of JSP 441 has been placed in the Library of the House. JSP 441 can also be found on the Gov.uk website:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/jsp-441-defence-records-management-policy-and-procedures--2</p><p>All files relating to Northern Ireland held at Swadlincote are assessed by the MOD and The National Archives officials for sensitivity and historic value. Those files deemed worthy of permanent preservation will be selected for transfer to The National Archives.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428658/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:16:26.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428658/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428658/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-17","Public Records: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his policy is on declassifying and transferring historical files relating to Northern Ireland held at Swadlincote to the National Archive under the 30-year rule.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","16555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428659","Department for Education","false","2015-11-24","<p>Since 1 September 2014, local authorities have been under a duty to develop and publish a Local Offer, which sets out the support they expect to be available for children and young people with special educational needs (SEN) or disabilities in their local area. This must provide clear, comprehensive, accessible and up-to-date information about the available provision and how to access it, and must make provision responsive to what parents and children want by involving them in its development. The Local Offer must include information about leisure activities, which could include information about play opportunities.</p><p>Play has an important role in supporting all young children to develop and prepare for later learning. The importance of play is recognised in the Early Years Foundation Stage framework, which states: âEach area of learning and development must be implemented through planned, purposeful play and through a mix of adult-led and child-initiated activity. Play is essential for childrenâs development, building their confidence as they learn to explore, to think about problems, and relate to others.â</p><p>Since September 2014, two year olds who have a statement of SEN, or an Education, Health and Care Plan, or who are receiving Disability Living Allowance, have also been entitled to 570 hours of free early education, to support their families.</p><p>For older children, the Equality Act 2010 requires all schools to publish an accessibility plan. These plans are about ensuring that all aspects of school life, including facilities used for play, are accessible to disabled pupils. In addition, local authorities are required to publish an accessibility strategy which must be published as part of their Local Offer.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428659/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:54:06.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428659/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428659/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-17","Children's Play: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the level of support available to help families with disabled children find appropriate play opportunities.","false","Biography information for John Glen","Salisbury","John Glen","16592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428660","Cabinet Office","false","2015-11-23","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428660/answer","Response to PQ 16348 and 16620.pdf","Response to PQ 16348 and 16620.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Domestic Assaults","UKSA Letter to Member - Domestic Assaults","16348","2015-11-23T09:20:05.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428660/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428660/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-17","Domestic Abuse: Pupils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many pupils are known to be (a) victims, (b) perpetrators of domestic assaults; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","16620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428661","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-24","<p>The terms of the Hinkley Point C Contract for difference (HPC CfD) will set out the mechanism for the Opex reopeners. If my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State decides to direct the Low Carbon Contracts Company Ltd to offer a CfD to HPC, the terms will be published (with commercially sensitive information removed) once it has been entered in to by the parties. The detailed terms of the HPC CfD are commercially sensitive at this time.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428661/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T17:23:37.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428661/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428661/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-17","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if she will specify the comparable operators whose costs would be taken into account prior to the Opex reopeners for the contract for difference relating to Hinkley Point C power station being triggered 15 and 25 years after the first reactor start date.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","16617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428662","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-25","<p>Recent major investments in the north of England include Siemens and APBâs investment in Hull, Offshore Structure Britain in Teesside and JDR Cables in Hartlepool. There has also been significant investment in operations and maintenance facilities. These investments are helping to deliver high quality and long term jobs to the region.</p><p><br></p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428662/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T14:37:22.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428662/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428662/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428662/answer/previousversion/31297","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-17","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate she has made of the effect that the offshore wind industry has on stimulating investment in the north of England.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","16627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428663","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-24","<p>As explained in DECCâs Departmental Minute of 21 October, a political shut down would be an action by a UK, EU or international Competent Authority which shutdown, or prevented the completion of, Hinkley Point C (HPC) â except where this action is done on grounds of protecting health, nuclear safety, security, environmental, nuclear transport or nuclear safeguards related matters. If my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State decides to direct the Low Carbon Contracts Company Ltd to offer a Contract for Difference to HPC, the terms of the contract will be published (with commercially sensitive information removed) once it has been entered in to by the parties.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428663/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T17:24:49.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428663/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428663/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-17","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what circumstances would constitute a political shutdown of the proposed Hinkley Point C power station by the EU or international competent authority which would trigger a payment to the operators of that power station.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","16616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428664","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-20","<p>The Department responded to the CMAâs provisional findings on 31 July (copy attached).</p><p>We are committed to implementing the final recommendations of the CMA and we currently expect their final report in April 2016.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428664/answer","DECC Response to CMA 31.07.15.pdf","DECC Response to CMA 31.07.15.pdf","DECC Response to CMA 31.07.15","DECC Response to CMA 31.07.15",,"2015-11-20T14:59:54.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428664/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428664/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-17","Energy: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps her Department has taken in response to the provisional report of the Competition and Markets Authority's findings on the energy market; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","16606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428665","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-25","<p>We continue to make progress towards our renewable energy target of 15% final energy consumption by 2020. Provisional figures show 6.3% of final energy consumption came from renewable sources for 2013 and 2014, against a target of 5.4%.</p><br /><p>Progress on renewable electricity generation has been particularly strong with over a quarter of electricity generated, between April and June this year, coming from renewable sources.</p><br /><p>The Spending Review will be announced on 25<sup>th</sup> November, and a Department for Transport consultation will be running next year on increasing the amount of renewable transport fuel. We will carefully consider the impacts of both on the UKâs progress towards the renewables target of 15%, including whether there will be a role for trading.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428665/answer",,,,,"16545","2015-11-25T14:39:47.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428665/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428665/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-17","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what specific changes are needed to her Department's policies to ensure that the UK meets the EU target of 15 per cent of energy to be sourced from renewable sources before 2020; and what the timetable is for implementing each of those changes.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","16546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428666","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-25","<p>We have received nearly 55,000 responses to the consultation. We currently estimate that just over 2,600 are unique and detailed responses; the rest are briefer and more uniform responses, generated by campaigns. We are currently analysing feedback submitted during the consultation and intend to publish a Government response as soon as possible.</p><p><br></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428666/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T14:36:57.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428666/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428666/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-17","Solar Power: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether her Department has received evidence on the effect of the feed-in tariff review on jobs in the solar industry.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","16547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428667","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-23","<p>Spending Round 2013 set the Departmentâs budget for 2015-16, including efficiency savings. Details can be found via the link below.</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/209036/spending-round-2013-complete.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/209036/spending-round-2013-complete.pdf</a></p><br /><p>Subsequently, on 4<sup>th</sup> June 2015, the Government announced further efficiency savings to be delivered in 2015-16. DECCâs contribution to that exercise was to find an addition Â£70M of efficiency savings.</p><p><br></p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428667/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T15:21:08.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428667/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428667/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428667/answer/previousversion/31295","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-17","Department of Energy and Climate Change: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what cost savings her Department is planning to make in the current financial year.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","16559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428668","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-23","<p>We are currently analysing feedback submitted during the Feed-in Tariff review consultation and intend to publish a Government response as soon as possible.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428668/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T15:20:13.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428668/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428668/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-17","Renewable Energy: Feed-in Tariffs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, pursuant to the Answer of 3 November 2015 to Question 14118, when she plans to respond to the consultation on the feed-in tariff review.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","16569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428669","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-25","<p>We continue to make progress towards our renewable energy target of 15% final energy consumption by 2020. Provisional figures show 6.3% of final energy consumption came from renewable sources for 2013 and 2014, against a target of 5.4%.</p><br /><p>Progress on renewable electricity generation has been particularly strong with over a quarter of electricity generated, between April and June this year, coming from renewable sources.</p><br /><p>The Spending Review will be announced on 25<sup>th</sup> November, and a Department for Transport consultation will be running next year on increasing the amount of renewable transport fuel. We will carefully consider the impacts of both on the UKâs progress towards the renewables target of 15%, including whether there will be a role for trading.</p><br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428669/answer",,,,,"16546","2015-11-25T14:39:47.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428669/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428669/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-17","Renewable Energy: Imports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what the (a) volume, (b) gross capital and (c) gross revenue costs of planned purchases of renewable energy is from other European countries.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","16545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428671","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-24","<p>The European Commission has issued proposals[1] on fishing opportunities to be agreed for 2016, which includes EU bass management measures for the commercial fishing and recreational sea angling sectors consisting of a moratorium on fishing for bass in the first six months, and reduced catch limits for the latter half of the year. The UK response to these proposals is being considered in advance of negotiations at the December Fisheries Council.</p><br /><p>The latest available assessment of the bass stock, from the International Council for the Exploration of the Sea, was published in June this year before the full set of EU bass management measures for 2015 was finalised in September. Its next assessment is due in June 2016.</p><br /><p><br></p><p>[1] <a href="http://eur-lex.europa.eu/resource.html?uri=cellar:f4d9701d-87b1-11e5-b8b7-01aa75ed71a1.0011.02/DOC_1&amp;format=PDF" target="_blank">http://eur-lex.europa.eu/resource.html?uri=cellar:f4d9701d-87b1-11e5-b8b7-01aa75ed71a1.0011.02/DOC_1&amp;format=PDF</a></p><br /><p><br> <br></p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428671/answer",,,,,"16562 ; 16563 ; 16564 ; 16783","2015-11-24T10:40:33.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428671/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428671/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-11-17","Fisheries: White Fish","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what measures she proposes to introduce to regulate commercial fishermen catching sea bass for the period from 1 January to 30 June 2016.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sheryll Murray","South East Cornwall","Mrs Sheryll Murray","16561"
