"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428682","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-25","<p>Improving the environment is essential for providing the natural resources that underpin our economic success. We also want to see businesses whose products improve the environment grow. As a member of the Informal Ministerial Group on the Northern Powerhouse, I have discussed with the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government and other Ministerial colleagues ways in which a healthy environment and economic growth in the north of England go together.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428682/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T10:27:05.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428682/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428682/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-11-17","Environment Protection: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the (a) Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government and (b) Chancellor of the Exchequer on improving the environment as part of the Northern Powerhouse initiative.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","16587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428683","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-20","<p>The Government is concerned by the violence directed towards those expressing secular or atheist views in Bangladesh. Ministers have been unequivocal in our condemnation of the murder of five secular bloggers and publishers in Bangladesh this year, and in calling for the Bangladesh government to protect those who face threats to their lives because of the views they have expressed. My noble Friend the right hon Baroness Anelay of St Johns, our High Commissioner in Dhaka and myself, in my statement on 7 August, have all expressed shock at the appalling murders and called for the perpetrators to be brought to justice and free speech protected. In my 14 August blog I said that Bangladesh is a secular country, with a rich tradition of freedom and religious tolerance. That should be commended, protected and preserved.</p><p>The United Nations Special Rapporteur on Freedom of Religion or Belief, Heiner Bielefeldt, visited Bangladesh from 31 August to 9 September. We look forward to the release of his report at the UN Human Rights Council in March 2016 and will encourage the government to consider all its recommendations carefully.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428683/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T13:57:18.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428683/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428683/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-17","Bangladesh: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of freedom of religion and belief in Bangladesh; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","16622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428684","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-20","<p>Protection of civilians in Syria, as well as those who have been forced to flee the country, is a priority for the UK. In the UN Security Council the UK has co-sponsored a number of humanitarian resolutions that call for an end to: indiscriminate attacks on civilians, including the use of barrel bombs; starvation as a method of warfare; and obstruction of the flow of humanitarian aid. Specifically, the UK played a key role in negotiating UN Security Council Resolution 2191, which has allowed the UN and its partners to deliver aid across Syriaâs borders to people who were previously denied access, including food for 2.1 million people and medical supplies for 2.5 million people. The UK will use its seat on the UN Security Council to push proactively for a renewal of Resolution 2191.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428684/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:26:43.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428684/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428684/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-17","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how the Government plans to use its position on the UN Security Council to facilitate diplomatic negotiations on protecting civilians in Syria.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","16557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428685","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>A twelve week public consultation ended on 27 October. Nearly 850 written responses were received from as far afield as Tanzania, Switzerland, Thailand, France, and of course the main Chagossian communities in the UK, Mauritius and Seychelles. Officials are continuing their analysis of these, and the results of meetings held with Chagossians in their own communities, to allow a decision on a way ahead soon.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428685/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T14:38:42.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428685/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428685/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-17","Ilois: Resettlement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when his Department plans to make an announcement regarding resettlement of the British Indian Ocean Territory by Chagos islanders.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","16549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428686","Department of Health","false","2015-11-24","<p>There were 11,674 community pharmacies in England at 31 March 2015. 95% of the population is within a 20 minute walk of a community pharmacy, with access greatest in the most deprived areas. It is not for the Department to determine or advise on how health and social care providers, including pharmacies, comply with equalities legislation. It is up to each pharmacy owner to ensure their pharmacy premises comply with the Equality Act 2010.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428686/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:56:30.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428686/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428686/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the number and accessibility of pharmacy facilities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","16575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428687","Department of Health","false","2015-11-25","<p>The Department has commissioned the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicineâs Public Health Research Consortium to conduct a study to explore patterns of prescribing for specific medicines that have a risk of dependence, using the Clinical Practice Research Datalink. These include: benzodiazepines; z-drugs; opioid-containing prescription drugs for pain; and the GABA-ergic drugs, pregabalin and gabapentin.</p><br /><p>This study will not assess dependence on such medicines, because being in receipt of a prescription is not indicative of dependence. However, it will seek to explore the circumstances in which prescriptions of medicines with a risk of dependence are issued. A better understanding of prescribing patterns is an important step in helping clinicians identify patients at risk of dependence on the medicines they prescribe.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428687/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T12:42:41.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428687/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428687/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Drugs: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Answer of 24 March 2015 to Question 227804, if his Department plans to commission further research on (a) patterns of long-term prescription of dependency-forming medicines and (b) the scale of addiction to benzodiazepines, z drugs and other such medicines.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","16566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428688","Department of Health","false","2015-11-25","<p>Public Health England is currently working with two local authorities and one other area which is part of a Clinical Commissioning Group who want to improve their responses to addiction to medicines. These improvements are wide-ranging and do not necessarily involve developing bespoke services for people affected by specific medicines. There are also other areas which are looking at how they respond to addiction to medicines locally.</p><br /><p>Local authorities are responsible for commissioning effective services to meet the need of their local populations which experience dependence on any medicines or drugs, including treatment for people dependent on prescription benzodiazepines and tranquillisers.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428688/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T12:52:57.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428688/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428688/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Prescription Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Answer of 11 March 2015 to Question 226385, how many local authorities supported by PHE are developing withdrawal services for people affected by addiction to prescription benzodiazepine and drug tranquilisers.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","16567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428689","Department of Health","false","2015-11-20","<p>Officials in the Department and across Government are working hard to understand pressures on the system and are considering adult social care expenditure and future demand as part of the Spending Review process. This includes modelling of the effect on adult social care of different funding allocations.</p><p>The Spending Review process will formally conclude on 25 November 2015, when the Chancellor will announce the outcome.</p><br /><p>The Department has already commissioned a full review of the Adult Social Care Relative Needs Formula (which is used to allocate funding to local authorities based on indicators such as need, population and wealth) from the Personal Social Services Research Unit (at the University of Kent and the London School of Economics) and LG Futures (a consultancy).</p><br /><p>As part of this review, 53 councils have contributed the most detailed data yet obtained for social care allocations. The researchers are currently writing up the research which will be published in due course.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428689/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:36:12.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428689/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428689/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Social Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what modelling his Department has undertaken of the effect on adult social care of different funding allocations for such services.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","16604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428690","Department of Health","false","2015-11-24","<p>The Department does not collect information about the number of complaints received or the number of adults with learning disabilities using day centres. Day centres are not regulated by the Care Quality Commission.</p><br />","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428690/answer",,,,,"16590","2015-11-24T16:42:56.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428690/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428690/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Day Centres: Learning Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many complaints about day centres for adults with learning disabilities his Department has received since the establishment of the Care Quality Commission.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","16589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428691","Department of Health","false","2015-11-24","<p>The Department does not collect information about the number of complaints received or the number of adults with learning disabilities using day centres. Day centres are not regulated by the Care Quality Commission.</p><br />","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428691/answer",,,,,"16589","2015-11-24T16:42:56.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428691/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428691/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Day Centres: Learning Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of adults with learning disabilities using day centres which are not regulated by the Care Quality Commission.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","16590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428692","Department of Health","false","2015-11-24","<p>The Care Quality Commission (CQC) is the independent regulator of health and adult social care in England. Under the Health and Social Care Act 2008 all providers of regulated activities, have to register with CQC and meet a set of fundamental standards of safety and quality below which care should never fall.</p><br /><p>The Department is responsible for setting in legislation both the scope of registration and the fundamental standards that registered providers must meet. These are set out in the Health and Social Care Act 2008 (Regulated Activities) Regulations 2014.</p><br /><p>The scope of registration is proportionate to risk and based on the activity being carried out rather than the setting. Day centres that carry on a regulated activity are required to register with CQC and to meet the fundamental standards. In most instances they will be registered to provide the regulated activity of personal care.</p><br /><p>The Department keeps the regulated activities under review to ensure that regulation by CQC is focused on those areas where the risks to service users are greatest. The Department has no current plans to require all providers of day centres to register with CQC.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428692/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T17:01:24.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428692/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428692/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Day Centres: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he plans to extend the remit of the Care Quality Commission to include the regulation of all day centres; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","16591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428693","Department of Health","false","2015-11-20","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State is not ruling out conciliation â however, we believe it is still possible to have meaningful talks. We have already sought independent views on contract reform â having asked the independent Review Body on Doctorsâ and Dentists Remuneration (DDRB) for recommendations which formed the basis of our offer, an offer which the British Medical Association have so far refused to talk about. Both the BMA and the Government gave evidence to the DDRB. We continue to urge the BMA to come back round the table, and there are no preconditions to any talks, though of course the Government reserves the right to make changes to contracts if no progress is made on the issues preventing a truly 7 day NHS. That was promised in the manifesto and endorsed by the British people at the last election.</p><p>The DDRB made 23 recommendations and proposed that these should be the basis for national level negotiations between the BMA and NHS Employers, which the Government accepted. The DDRBâs report was published in July this year.</p><p>The BMA has refused to accept these independent recommendations as the basis for negotiations. The Government continues to urge the BMA to return to talks and to work in partnership with NHS Employers to agree a new contract that works for junior doctors and patients<strong>.</strong></p><br />","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428693/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:48:26.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428693/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428693/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Junior Doctors: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he has considered referring the junior doctors' contract dispute to ACAS.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","16598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428694","Department of Health","false","2015-11-25","<p>No assessment has been made of compliance by doctors with the four-week recommended maximum prescribing period for benzodiazepines and z drugs since 2011. Guidance on the prescribing of benzodiazepines and âzâ drugs can be found in the British National Formulary.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428694/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T12:46:34.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428694/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428694/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Prescription Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of compliance by doctors with the four-week recommended maximum prescribing period for benzodiazepines and z drugs since 2011.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","16618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428695","Home Office","false","2015-11-23","<p>Tackling violence against women and girls remains a priority for this Government. Allocation of funding for domestic and sexual violence support services is dependent on the outcome of the Spending Review.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428695/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T17:22:31.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428695/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428695/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428695/answer/previousversion/31147","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Domestic Abuse and Sexual Offences: Victim Support Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what funding her Department plans to allocate to domestic and sexual violence support services after April 2016; and for how long she plans for that funding to be available.","false","Biography information for Andrew Percy","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy","16626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428696","Home Office","false","2015-11-23","<p>The previous Government signed the Istanbul Convention in June 2012 and this Government remains committed to its ratification.</p><p>The UK already complies with the vast majority of the articles through our comprehensive work to protect women and girls from violence, including criminalising forced marriage as required by the Convention. However, primary legislation will be required to comply with the extra-territorial jurisdiction provisions in Article 44 of the Convention before ratification. The Government is liaising with the devolved administrations about ratification, including any further legislative steps necessary.</p><p>The Government takes its international commitments very seriously and will only commit to such ratification when we are absolutely satisfied that we comply with all articles. We will continue to lead efforts to tackle violence against women and girls, end Female Genital Mutilation and combat early and forced marriage, both at home and abroad.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428696/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T16:57:23.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428696/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428696/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428696/answer/previousversion/31140","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Council of Europe Convention on Preventing and Combating Violence against Women and Domestic Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to ratify the Council of Europe's Istanbul Convention on Preventing and Combating Violence against Women and Domestic Violence.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","16621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428698","Home Office","false","2015-12-02","<p>Pregnant women are not normally detained. The only exceptions to this general rule are where removal is imminent and medical advice does not suggest the womanâs baby is due before the expected removal date.</p><p>Fitness to travel by air is assessed on a case by case basis using guidance from the International Air Transportation Association (IATA). The guidance states that for a single, uncomplicated pregnancy, travel could be appropriate without a medical certificate up to 37 weeks.</p><p>Yarlâs Wood immigration removal centre has a dedicated Care Suite that offers enhanced care to vulnerable and pregnant women, staffed by a dedicated female member of staff. Midwives from NHS Bedford Hospital Trust visit the centre once a week and the centre's GP or nurses can be accessed 7 days a week and can refer any specific concerns to the ante natal clinic, Early Pregnancy Unit in hospital or other appropriate service if necessary. The centre also has a Pregnancy Liaison Officer who provides a range of support and welfare services to pregnant detainees.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428698/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T14:20:26.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428698/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428698/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre: Pregnancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what provisions are in place to safeguard the welfare of pregnant women in Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","16596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428699","Home Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>The Home Office does not record information in relation to homelessness. We do encounter rough sleepers during enforcement operations and, depending on the individual circumstances, non-UK rough sleepers can be removed or deported. In these situations, the Immigration Enforcement teams will ensure that vulnerable individuals are also connected to support services in their home countries.</p><p>For vulnerable individuals who are sleeping rough on the streets, there are locally funded reconnection services they can approach voluntarily to help them return to their home countries voluntarily and connect into support services there. We do not hold data on those who are returned using this service.</p><p>Therefore, any information we hold does not provide a complete and accurate picture of those who have returned home.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428699/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:43:57.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428699/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428699/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428699/answer/previousversion/31141","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Homelessness: Repatriation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people from (a) EU and (b) non-EU countries who have been classified as homeless have been returned to their home countries in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","16607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428700","Home Office","false","2015-11-26","<p>The actions which stemmed from the National Groupâs work have been incorporated into a cross-Whitehall CSA Programme which includes the actions from the âTackling CSEâ report published in March 2015, and the WeProtect Summit in December 2014.</p><p>Good progress is being made across the range of commitments in the CSA Programme, including that to establish a new national response unit to help local areas when child sexual exploitation is a particular concern. The Government will publish a progress report on all actions within the Programme one year on from the publication of âTackling CSEâ.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428700/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T17:44:54.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428700/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428700/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress the National Group on Sexual Violence Against Children and Vulnerable People has made on establishing a Child Sexual Exploitation Response Unit; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen McPartland","Stevenage","Stephen McPartland","16619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428701","Home Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>The level and distribution of counter-terrorism resources across the country is informed by advice from the police and security and intelligence agencies on assessments of what is needed to counter the threat. This is regularly kept under review. For security reasons we do not publish a breakdown of counter-terrorism resources by region.</p><p>In the Spending Round 2013, specific funding for counter-terrorism policing was protected at Â£564.3 million for each of the years 2014-15 and 2015-16. We are also providing an additional Â£14.9 million in 2015-16 to the police to strengthen capabilities in response to the increased threat from terrorism.</p><p>In the Summer Budget on 8 July, we committed to protecting overall counter-terrorism spending across the course of the next Spending Review Period. On 16 November we said we would go further. Through the Strategic Defence and Security Review, we will make new funding available for the security and intelligence agencies to provide for an additional 1,900 officers â an increase of 15% - to better respond to the threat we face from international terrorism, cyber-attacks and other global risks.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428701/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T15:47:06.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428701/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428701/answer","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428701/answer/previousversion/31138","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Counter-terrorism: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will review the number of counter-terrorism officials in the West Midlands; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","16603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428703","Home Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>All detainees at immigration removal centres are able to access legal advice through a duty solicitor scheme provided by the Legal Aid Agency.</p><p>Her Majestyâs Chief Inspector of Prisons (HMCIP) inspected Yarlâs Wood between 13 April and 1 May 2015 and reported that waiting times for duty advice surgeries were short.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428703/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T15:38:40.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428703/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428703/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre: Legal Representation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many women held in Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre have legal representation.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","16576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428704","Home Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>In total 420 individuals of the listed nationalities were confirmed as victims of trafficking between 2010 and 2015 of which 338 had an associated asylum claim split as follows: a) Benin [1], b) Nigeria [264], c) Uganda [62] and d) Zimbabwe [11]. The proportion of successful asylum claims for those cases where a decision had been made were: a) Benin [0% (0)], b) Nigeria [74% (156)], c) Uganda [85% (46)] and d) Zimbabwe [88% (7)]</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428704/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:58:39.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428704/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428704/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Asylum: Africa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of victims of human trafficking from (a) Benin, (b) Nigeria, (c) Uganda and (d) Zimbabwe who applied for asylum were successful in their application between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","16583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428705","Department of Health","false","2015-11-25","<p>In April 2015, Public Health England, NHS England, and Home Office Immigration Enforcement jointly published a National Partnership Agreement which outlines shared commitments and priorities across the three organisations relating to the health and wellbeing of people in detention in the immigration removal estate. This includes a joint priority to improve the pro-active detection, surveillance and management of infectious diseases in Immigration Removal Centres (IRCs), particularly in respect of blood-borne viruses (BBVs) and tuberculosis (TB), and to improve capability to detect and respond to outbreaks and incidents.</p><p>A programme of work to implement the provisions of the National Partnership Agreement is being taken forward by the three organisations. Use of new technology is being explored in some IRCs including using digital x-ray technology to detect active TB disease in the lungs as well as blood tests to detect both latent TB and BBV infection.</p><br /> <br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428705/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T17:04:53.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428705/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428705/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Detainees: Infectious Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his Department's policy is on testing detainees for infectious diseases such as TB.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","16550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428706","Home Office","false","2015-12-02","<p>Provisional management information showing the number of women who have been handcuffed when taken to hospital from Yarlâs Wood immigration removal centre over the requested period is detailed in the table below:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Month</p></td><td><p>Number of Handcuffed Hospital Moves</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The increased figure in October 2015 was not due to any change in policy. These cases have been reviewed by the Home Office Use of Force Monitor to ensure that the use of handcuffs was appropriate. The review established that each case had been subject to an individual risk assessment, in accordance with standard policy, and that handcuffs were used on the basis of that outcome of that assessment.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428706/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T14:14:32.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428706/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428706/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre: Hospitals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many women taken to hospital from Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre have been handcuffed in transit in each of the last six months.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","16551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428707","Home Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>Individuals who have been identified as victims of trafficking by the competent authorities are normally considered suitable for detention in only very exceptional circumstances, which include cases where there is a risk of public harm. This data is not collected centrally and accurate figures are not available. Once a person is detained their continued detention remains under review by the Home Office at least at monthly intervals, and earlier in response to any change of circumstances that might have a material effect on their detention.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428707/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:56:34.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428707/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428707/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre: Human Trafficking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many detainees held in Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre (a) claim that they are victims of human trafficking and (b) have been identified by the National Referral Mechanism as victims of human trafficking.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","16552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428708","Home Office","false","2015-12-02","<p>For the period 1 January 2015 to 30 June 2015 provisional management information shows that 84 women were recorded as refusing food or fluid at Yarlâs Wood immigration removal centre (IRC).</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428708/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T14:16:09.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428708/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428708/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre: Hunger Strikes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many women detained in Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre went on hunger strike in 2015.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","16553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428709","Department for International Development","false","2015-11-24","<p>A document describing âDFIDâs approach to LGBT rightsâ will be published on UK Government website by the end of 2015. A theory of change will be available with this.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428709/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T15:41:07.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428709/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428709/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-11-17","Developing Countries: LGBT People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department is planning to publish an LGBT Theory of Change.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","16568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428710","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-20","<p>As I stated in response to Question 14066, although the Criminal Cases Review Commission is funded by my Department, it is entirely independent of Government, and Ministers cannot, and should not, intervene in its reviews or decisions. Since there is no action I can take, I do not believe a meeting with the Hon. Member would be helpful.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428710/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T10:55:42.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428710/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428710/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-11-17","Criminal Cases Review Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 3 November 2015 to Question 14066, what accountability mechanisms are in place for the Criminal Cases Review Commission; and if he will meet the hon. Member for Sefton Central to discuss the case of James Thompson.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","16560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428711","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-20","<p>This information could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428711/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T10:30:03.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428711/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428711/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-11-17","New Roads and Street Works Act 1991","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prosecutions and convictions have been obtained under sections 60 and 79 of the New Roads and Street Works Act 1991 since that Act came into force.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","16609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428712","Home Office","false","2015-11-25","<p>The UK and the Republic of Ireland have long enjoyed a Common Travel Area (CTA) free of routine border controls. However, there are long-established and effective working relationships between the police and intelligence agencies in both the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland to mitigate threats. The Government takes protecting our border security very seriously, and there is a high level of collaboration on work with the Republic of Ireland to also strengthen the CTAâs external border.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428712/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T14:37:23.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428712/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428712/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Counter-terrorism: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what arrangements are in place for the Government and the Northern Ireland Executive to cooperate to counter the Islamic terrorist threat and the potential utilisation by such terrorists of the land border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","16571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428713","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-11-25","<p>It would not be appropriate for me to comment on these matters which are the responsibility of the Security and Intelligence Agencies.</p><br />","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428713/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T15:32:58.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428713/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428713/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-11-17","MI5: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether proposals to expand the Security Service include the expansion of its facilities and additional recruitment in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","16572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428714","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-11-25","<p>I have regular discussions with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on a range of issues, including his plans for the Northern Powerhouse, which is about building a strong economy from which all parts of the United Kingdom can benefit.</p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428714/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T15:34:56.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428714/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428714/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-11-17","Economic Growth: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on how Northern Ireland can benefit from contributing to the Northern Powerhouse.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","16573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428715","Scotland Office","false","2015-11-23","<p>The Scotland Office engages with the Department for Culture, Media and Sport regularly on a range of important issues, including the Big Lottery Fund. The Parliamentary under Secretary of State, Lord Dunlop, met with the Big Lottery Fund in Edinburgh on 14 September.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428715/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T15:42:28.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428715/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428715/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-11-17","Big Lottery Fund: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for the Department for Culture, Media and Sport on the level of funding for the Big Lottery Fund.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","16640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428717","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-20","<p>Section 80 of the New Roads and Street Works Act 1991 contains a duty on persons carrying out works in the carriageway. As the question indicates, this has never been brought into force. It concerns occasions where a person undertaking works in the street finds apparatus belonging to an undertaker that does not appear or differs from the underground asset records provided. In such cases, the person would be required to take steps to inform the owner, or keep a record of its location and inform the relevant local authority of the nature of what they have found and its location.</p><br /><p>The associated section 79 (Records of location of apparatus) of the Act was brought into force in 2003. This section provides that those with apparatus under the street must maintain records of that apparatus, and provide it to those requesting it with a legitimate interest.</p><br /><p>Some years ago, the industry considered how the requirements in section 80 might operate in practice if they were brought into force. I am aware that at the time, those undertaking street works felt that there would be challenges in identifying the asset owner and conveying the information in a way that would provide an accurate and reliable record for the future. This process could delay completion of the works, causing additional congestion to traffic and adding cost to the job. These consequences conflict with the aims of minimising disruption and cost in carrying out street works. The range of methods used to maintain records, and inconsistency in how the information could be conveyed raised concerns about the feasibility of doing this, and future liability issues.</p><br /><p>No further consideration has been given to this matter recently.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428717/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T13:38:23.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428717/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428717/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-17","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reasons section 80 of the New Roads and Street Works Act 1991 has not been brought into force.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","16610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428718","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-20","<p>Investment in this countryâs transport infrastructure is vital for long-term economic growth. This is why the Government is committing to long-term investment in the Northern Powerhouse, in road and rail schemes, and is legislating to create Sub-National Transport Bodies.</p><br /><p>The Governmentâs <em>Road Investment Strategy (RIS) for the 2015 to 2020 Road Period</em> sets out plans for road schemes across the country. The strategy document is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/road-investment-strategy-for-the-2015-to-2020-road-period" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/road-investment-strategy-for-the-2015-to-2020-road-period</a>.</p><br /><p>A scheme for delivery in the first Road Period in Merseyside is the A5036 Princess Way â access to Port of Liverpool, a comprehensive upgrade to improve the main link between the Port of Liverpool and motorway network. Other schemes benefitting the wider Merseyside area include the upgrade to Smart Motorway of the M53 junctions 5 to 11 and the M6 junctions 21a to 26. Additionally, junction 22 of the M6 will be upgraded.</p><br /><p>Details of Local Growth Funds for the Merseyside area, which includes St Helens, are set out in the <em>Liverpool City Region: additional Growth Deal funding factsheet</em>, which is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/liverpool-city-region-growth-deal" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/liverpool-city-region-growth-deal</a>.</p><br /><p>This Growth Deal includes various transport schemes, in particular over Â£50m of government investment in key transport connections into and within Liverpool City Centre, revitalising the north of the city and better connecting Liverpoolâs iconic waterfront to the city centre. Additionally funding has been allocated to the A5300 Knowsley Expressway to maximise the benefits of the New Mersey crossing and access to Liverpool Airport; plus funding for development of a new station at Maghull North, improving transport across north Liverpool.</p><br /><p>The Government has also made a significant financial commitment to the Mersey Gateway Bridge which is currently under construction and which will improve accessibility across the wider Liverpool city region area. The Thornton to Switch Island link road in Sefton, to relieve congestion in the area and improve highway access between Southport and the North-West motorway system, has also recently been completed after receiving Â£14.5 million of government funding.</p><br /><p>The Liverpool City Region Combined Authority has been allocated around Â£88million in local highways maintenance funding for the period 2015/16 to 2020/21, which builds on the around Â£70million of local highways maintenance funding invested in Merseyside from 2010/11 to 2014/15.</p><br /><p>St Helens and Liverpool City Region will benefit from the North of England Rail Infrastructure Upgrade Programme. North West Electrification has recently been completed between Liverpool and Manchesterand Liverpool and Wigan and Northern Electric services serve the St Helens North constituency.</p><br /><p>Liverpool City Region recently signed a devolution deal which will allow local authorities to take on responsibility for local issues on an unprecedented level. The region will also have an elected Mayor. This devolution of powers is part of the Governmentâs strategy to create a Northern Powerhouse which will enable the North to work together and become greater than the sum of its parts.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428718/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T13:33:22.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428718/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428718/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-17","Transport: Merseyside","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what investment in transport services the Government plans to make in (a) St Helens North constituency and (b) Merseyside as part of the Northern Powerhouse initiative.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","16605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428721","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-24","<p><strong></strong>This information is not held by the Department. Under the Welsh rail devolution arrangements, the Welsh Government is responsible for the day to day management of the Arriva Trains Wales franchise, including services to and from Neston.</p><br />","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428721/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T15:08:02.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428721/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428721/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-17","Railways: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many train services through Neston have been cancelled since August 2015; and what the reason was for the cancellation in each such case.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","16574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428722","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-24","<p>The statutory minimum bus travel concession scheme applies to off-peak travel when there is likely to be unused operational capacity on buses. Concessionary bus travel applies to bus journeys made between 9.30am and 11.00pm Monday to Friday and all day at weekends and on bank holidays. These times were set out in legislation in the Transport Act 2000. Whilst I appreciate that concessionary pass holders might wish to use buses before 9.30am, in the current economic climate there are no plans to extend the statutory scheme to include peak time travel.</p><br /><p>I would point out that the statutory minimum is indeed just that â a minimum. It remains very much open to each local authority to decide whether to offer its residents local concessions over and above the statutory minimum, including peak hour concessions.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428722/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T15:13:38.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428722/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428722/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-17","Bus Services: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will extend free bus travel for people with disabilities to include peak hours.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","16579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428723","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-23","<p>The Department for Transportâs Best Practice Guidance for taxi and private hire licensing advises local authorities that the safety of the public depends on authorities having effective enforcement mechanisms in place.</p><br /><p>The Guidance adds that it is desirable to ensure that taxi and PHV enforcement is at least partially directed to the late night period when problems such as touting and illegal plying for hire are most prevalent.</p><br /><p>It is for local licensing authorities to determine how they allocate resources for enforcement, which will vary according to local circumstances. Licensing authorities are also advised to liaise closely with the police when undertaking enforcement activity.</p><br />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428723/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T15:13:16.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428723/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428723/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-17","Taxis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what guidance he provides to local authorities on the enforcement of the prohibition on private hire vehicles plying for hire; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","16580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428724","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-24","<p>After the Silk Commission recommendations, further powers in Transport are to be devolved to the Welsh Government. We are currently in discussion with the Welsh Government about the future of the Wales and Borders franchise, including the cross-border services such as those serving Neston.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428724/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T15:03:31.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428724/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428724/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-17","Railways: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to ensure a more reliable train service is provided to Neston.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","16570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428725","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-20","<p>The Mayor has raised the Transport for London Bill with the Secretary of State in writing, and at several of their regular meetings.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428725/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T13:58:29.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428725/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428725/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-17","Transport for London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what representations his Department received from the Mayor of London on the Transport for London Bill.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","16558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428728","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-20","<p>Since April 2013, arrangements have been in place to identify potential overlapping payments between Universal Credit Live Service and Housing Benefit. Any cases identified are referred to Universal Credit for resolution with the appropriate Local Authority.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428728/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:51:11.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428728/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428728/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-17","Universal Credit: Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what reports he has received of claimants receiving overlapping payments of both universal credit and housing benefit; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","16608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428730","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-11-24","<p>Yes, this change will be made as planned in April 2016. The Universal Credit and Miscellaneous Amendments Regulations 2015 include the legislative change which will bring this into force.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428730/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T11:11:51.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428730/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428730/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-11-17","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to page three of the document Universal Credit: increasing the childcare offer, published by his Department in December 2014, whether his Department remains on course to introduce childcare support into universal credit at 85 per cent of costs in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","16613"
