t)</p><p><sup>2</sup> Includes the basic award and all supplementary allowances and one off payments.</p><p><sup>3 </sup>Figures are provisional and may be subject to minor change as a result of subsequent retrospective payments.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428795/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T12:39:56.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428795/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428795/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Midwives: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many student midwives were in receipt of a bursary in each of the last 10 years for which figures are available; what the average bursary paid to a student midwife was in each of those years; and what the total cost to the public purse in bursaries paid to student midwives was in each such year.","false","Biography information for Maria Caulfield","Lewes","Maria Caulfield","16671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428796","Department of Health","false","2015-11-25","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guidance <em>Chronic kidney disease in adults: assessment and management,</em> published in July 2014, sets out best practice for clinicians on the diagnosis, treatment care and support of patients with chronic kidney disease (CKD). The advice covers monitoring for those patients at risk; pharmacological management and referral where appropriate.</p><br /><p>As highlighted in NICEâs guidance on acute kidney injury (AKI), published in August 2013, AKI is now increasingly seen in primary care in people without any acute illness and it is important that awareness of the condition should be raised among primary care health professionals, such as general practitioners. The best practice guidance emphasises early intervention and stresses the importance of risk assessment and prevention, early recognition and treatment. Both sets of NICE guidance can be found at the following links:</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg169" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg169</a></p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg182" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg182</a></p><br /><p>In addition, to support clinicians in training the Royal College of Physicians has worked in partnership with Health Education Englandâs e-Learning for Healthcare to develop Kidn-e; an e-learning resource to provide easily accessible e-learning to support on the most common and important renal conditions, such as AKI and CKD.</p><br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428796/answer",,,,,"16743","2015-11-25T12:50:05.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428796/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428796/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Kidney Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps have been taken to encourage the implementation of improvement interventions relating to chronic kidney disease since April 2015.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","16742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428797","Department of Health","false","2015-11-25","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guidance <em>Chronic kidney disease in adults: assessment and management,</em> published in July 2014, sets out best practice for clinicians on the diagnosis, treatment care and support of patients with chronic kidney disease (CKD). The advice covers monitoring for those patients at risk; pharmacological management and referral where appropriate.</p><br /><p>As highlighted in NICEâs guidance on acute kidney injury (AKI), published in August 2013, AKI is now increasingly seen in primary care in people without any acute illness and it is important that awareness of the condition should be raised among primary care health professionals, such as general practitioners. The best practice guidance emphasises early intervention and stresses the importance of risk assessment and prevention, early recognition and treatment. Both sets of NICE guidance can be found at the following links:</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg169" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg169</a></p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg182" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/guidance/cg182</a></p><br /><p>In addition, to support clinicians in training the Royal College of Physicians has worked in partnership with Health Education Englandâs e-Learning for Healthcare to develop Kidn-e; an e-learning resource to provide easily accessible e-learning to support on the most common and important renal conditions, such as AKI and CKD.</p><br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428797/answer",,,,,"16742","2015-11-25T12:50:05.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428797/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428797/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Kidney Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans his Department has to improve the level of knowledge and awareness amongst GPs of acute kidney injury; and who he plans will lead those initiatives.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","16743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428798","Department of Health","false","2015-11-20","<p>The Government has not established a working party in relation to the Off-Patent Drugs Bill. We did hold a roundtable event in February 2015 with key stakeholders including charities and agreed several follow up actions. We have now agreed additional further actions:</p><p>- arrange a further roundtable event specifically for those charities who would like to explore the Bill in more detail;</p><p>- input in to the work of the Off-Patent Drugs Bill All Party Parliamentary Group; and</p><p>- hold a Ministerial drop-in session on 30 November, for those who would like to discuss the Bill further. This will be hosted by myself.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428798/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:51:05.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428798/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428798/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer given by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Care Quality during Oral Questions on 17 November 2015 on the establishment of a working party to examine issues regarding the availability of off-patent, repurposed drugs, when the working party was established; what the working party's scope and terms of reference are; which organisations and individuals have been invited to join the working party; and when the next meeting of the working party will be convened.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","16729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428799","Department of Health","false","2015-11-25","<br /><p>Providers of regulated health and social care services must be registered with the Care Quality Commission and comply with certain fundamental standards, including those relating to the employment of fit and proper persons.</p><br /><p>In the National Health Service, employing organisations have the overarching responsibility for auditing and monitoring compliance of third party suppliers of temporary workers (including locum doctors) to ensure that they operate to the same level of standards in relation to undertaking pre-appointment checks as outlined by the NHS Employment Check Standards. Under the framework agreements, all external staffing providers (including contractors and agencies) are required to provide assurances that they have robust recruitment processes in place in line with the NHS Employment Check Standards.</p><br /><p>Care workers also routinely use agencies to secure employment or apply to care homes and care providers directly. Employers in the care sector have a duty of care to patients and their families to take all appropriate action to ensure employees have the appropriate credentials to enable them to work in the sector. In cases of direct payment, where the council pays the care-recipient directly to employ a carer, this responsibility falls to the care recipient.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428799/answer",,,,,"16659","2015-11-25T17:17:56.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428799/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428799/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Employment Agencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the quality and rigour of checks made by locum agencies of the character and credentials of staff to be provided to the NHS or social services; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","16660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428800","Department of Health","false","2015-11-25","<br /><p>Providers of regulated health and social care services must be registered with the Care Quality Commission and comply with certain fundamental standards, including those relating to the employment of fit and proper persons.</p><br /><p>In the National Health Service, employing organisations have the overarching responsibility for auditing and monitoring compliance of third party suppliers of temporary workers (including locum doctors) to ensure that they operate to the same level of standards in relation to undertaking pre-appointment checks as outlined by the NHS Employment Check Standards. Under the framework agreements, all external staffing providers (including contractors and agencies) are required to provide assurances that they have robust recruitment processes in place in line with the NHS Employment Check Standards.</p><br /><p>Care workers also routinely use agencies to secure employment or apply to care homes and care providers directly. Employers in the care sector have a duty of care to patients and their families to take all appropriate action to ensure employees have the appropriate credentials to enable them to work in the sector. In cases of direct payment, where the council pays the care-recipient directly to employ a carer, this responsibility falls to the care recipient.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428800/answer",,,,,"16660","2015-11-25T17:17:56.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428800/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428800/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Employment Agencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what checks locum agencies are required to make when they sub-contract the provision of staff to other locum agencies for temporary workers in the NHS or social services; what steps are taken to ensure proper checks are made on the quality and character of such staff; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","16659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428801","Department of Health","false","2015-11-20","<p>That information is not available centrally.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428801/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:47:07.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428801/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428801/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Hyperactivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many children in each parliamentary constituency are diagnosed with ADHD.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","16725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428802","Department of Health","false","2015-11-20","<p>The Department has provided the following financial support for the National Suicide Prevention Alliance since its establishment in 2012:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Funding</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>Â£60,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>Â£60,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>Â£60,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>Â£180,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>Source: Department of Health</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p><br /> <br />","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428802/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:40:08.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428802/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428802/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","National Suicide Prevention Alliance: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what financial support his Department has provided to the National Suicide Prevention Alliance in each of the last five years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","16697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428803","Department of Health","false","2015-11-20","<p>Officials in the Department of Health have liaised with the Department for Work and Pensions as the lead Department for the Family Test to embed it and encourage routine use of the Test. This has included training officials on applying the Test, disseminating relevant evidence, learning materials and best practice.</p><br /><p>The Family Test was announced by the Prime Minister in August 2014 and introduced in October 2014 through the publication of guidance for officials - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/368894/family-test-guidance.pdf" target="_blank">Family Test Guidance</a>.</p><br /><p>The objective of the Test is to introduce a family perspective to the policy making process, specifically to make the potential impacts on family functioning and relationships explicit.</p><br /><p>The Department of Health is working to raise awareness of the Family Test amongst its policy staff, so that the impact of policy on the family is considered as a matter of course. We have highlighted the Family Test through the Policy Kit, an online resource for the Department of Health policy officials. The Family Test is also highlighted in policy induction training, which is available to staff who are new to policy roles in the Department of Health.</p><br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428803/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T13:49:54.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428803/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428803/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Department of Health: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to embed the Family Test into its policy making.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","16698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428804","Department of Health","false","2015-11-20","<p>We have committed to achieving parity of esteem for mental and physical health and improving access to mental health services for all people. We are implementing the first waiting times for mental health services to ensure more people have access to care when they need it and we have increased access to talking therapies through the Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme.</p><br /><p>We know that men can sometimes be a hard to reach group for some mental health issues such as reducing the risk of suicide and reducing stigma and encouraging men to seek help for their mental health problems.</p><br /><p>We continue to provide financial support to the Time to Change programme which aims to reduce the stigma around mental health and we provide financial support to the National Suicide Prevention Alliance, which involves organisations from across Government, industry and the community, voluntary and charitable sectors to support delivery of the National Suicide Prevention Strategy. Men are highlighted as a high risk group within the National Strategy for whom our suicide prevention activities should be prioritised.</p><br /> <br />","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428804/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:35:07.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428804/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428804/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Mental Health Services: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that men make use of mental health services when they need them; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","16694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428805","Department of Health","false","2015-12-01","<p>In July, NHS England and the NHS Five Year Forward View partners announced eight urgent and emergency care vanguards. This included the South Devon and Torbay System Resilience Group.</p><br /><p>The new care models programme team visited the vanguard on 21 October 2015. This was an opportunity for the new care models programme team and vanguard team to jointly explore the vanguardâs proposals in more detail and to better understand the challenges they may face in delivering them.</p><br /><p>As the vanguard is still in its mobilisation phase, the new care models team cannot, at this stage, comment in detail on progress. However, from visits and assessments carried out to date, the new care models programme team has stated that it is clear that the vanguard has ambitious plans, a clear vision and is moving at pace. This will enable it to establish the infrastructure required to deliver new models of care effectively, building on existing local relationships and structures and good practice.</p><br />","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428805/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-01T16:22:26.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428805/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428805/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Health Services: Devon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent assessment he has made of progress in the urgent and emergency care vanguard run by South Devon and Torbay System Resilience Group.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","16731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428806","Department of Health","false","2015-12-01","<p>The Five Year Forward View published by NHS England sets out the healthcare strategy for the whole of England, including rural areas. Rural areas have their own health needs, which should be taken into account in planning and developing healthcare services.All healthcare services will benefit from the Governmentâs commitment of an additional Â£10 billion for the National Health Service by 2020, to back the NHSâs own plan for the future Five Year Forward View.</p><br /> <br />","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428806/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-01T17:12:03.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428806/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428806/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Health Services: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to develop a strategy for rural healthcare.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","16732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428807","Department of Health","false","2015-12-01","<p>There are now 50 vanguards across England, the majority of which are in localities that span both rural and urban areas. These include Dorset, Northumbria, Cheshire, Hertfordshire, Hampshire, Somerset, Cambridgeshire, Leicestershire, West Yorkshire and Devon.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p><br />","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428807/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-01T16:25:04.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428807/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428807/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Health Services: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether there are any vanguards in rural areas.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","16733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428808","Department of Health","false","2015-11-20","<p>Children and young peopleâs mental health is a priority area for this Government and it is committed to delivering the vision set out in Future in Mind, the report published jointly by the Department and NHS England in March 2015. This is supported by an additional investment of Â£1.4 billion over the next five years.</p><br /><p>Progress has been made on many of the key proposals set out in Future in Mind. One key proposal in Future in Mind is that Local Transformation Plans for Children and Young Peopleâs Mental Health and Wellbeing should be produced covering the full spectrum of mental health issues. Plans covering all clinical commissioning groups areas in the country are currently being assured by NHS Englandâs regional teams. Funding will be released subject to satisfactory assessment.</p><br /><p>Work is in progress to strengthen the capacity and capability of workforce and to improve data and information in order to deliver the vision set out in Future in Mind by 2020. In addition, the Children and Young People's Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme is continuing to be rolled out across the country.</p><br /><p>Progress has also been made on making help and support to children and young people available online through the launch of an online hub for children and young people on the NHS Choices website and further investment made into a campaign to reduce stigma and discrimination as proposed in Future in Mind.</p><br />","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428808/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:28:02.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428808/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428808/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made on implementing the aspirations in NHS England's report entitled, The Future in Mind, published in October 2012.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","16651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428809","Department of Health","false","2015-11-20","<p>I regularly meet with Department for Education Ministers regarding the progress on delivering the vision set out in Future in Mind to improve the mental health of all children and young people. This includes the provision of therapeutic support for victims of child sexual exploitation, bereavement and abuse.</p><br />","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428809/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:37:24.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428809/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428809/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with Ministers in the Department of Education on the provision of specialist mental health services for children and young people who have been victims of (a) child sexual exploitation, (b) bereavement and (c) abuse.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","16652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428810","Department of Health","true","2015-11-20","<p>NHS Englandâs specialised commissioning total spend on contracts with independent sector mental health providers is as follows:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Spend (Â£ million)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>478</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>581</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>576</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>Note: figures are based on contract values.</p><p>This expenditure relates to a number of different service types including: adult secure services; eating disorder services, gender identity services, child and adolescent mental health in patient services.</p><p><del class="ministerial">Details of local clinical commissioning group spend with independent sector providers is not collected centrally.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial"> <p><ins class="ministerial">The total NHS expenditure on non-NHS providers is collected centrally, and is published on page 47 of the Departmentâs annual report, available from:</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial"><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/447002/DH_accounts_14-15_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/447002/DH_accounts_14-15_web.pdf</a></ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">This report divides providers by type (i.e. independent sector providers, voluntary organisations) â it does not specify the different types of services provided.</ins></p></ins></p> <br /><p><br /></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428810/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:43:09.787Z","2016-01-06T10:24:57.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428810/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428810/answer","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428810/answer/previousversion/31280","Biography information for Alistair Burt","17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the cost to the NHS of NHS mental health patients being treated in non-NHS institutions has been in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","16648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428811","Department of Health","false","2015-11-24","<p>The latest available information provided by Health Education England shows that there were 6,624 student midwives in training in England at 31 March 2015.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428811/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:48:22.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428811/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428811/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Midwives: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the total population of student midwives in England was in the latest year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Maria Caulfield","Lewes","Maria Caulfield","16654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428812","Department of Health","false","2015-11-20","<p>Ministers in the Department of Health and Department of Work and Pensions have not had any recent discussions about the effect of sanctions on the mental health of people who have been so sanctioned.</p><br /><p>However, Ministers have many discussions with stakeholders about a range of issues, and the Secretary of State for Health and Secretary of State for Work and Pensions met on 3 June and agreed to greater cross government working between their respective Departments. Following that meeting, the Department of Health and Department for Work and Pensions Work and Health Unit was created to improve the health and employment outcomes of benefit claimants.</p><br /><p>We know that people come into contact with the welfare system at a time when they may be vulnerable because of unemployment and its associated consequences. The Department for Work and Pensions provides guidance and training for staff to help them identify and support people who may be vulnerable.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428812/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T13:37:30.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428812/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428812/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Mental Health: Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with Ministers in the Department for Work and Pensions on the effect of sanctions on the mental health of people who have been so sanctioned.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","16649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428813","Department of Health","false","2015-11-20","<p>The setting of a blanket waiting time target for children and young peopleâs mental health is not feasible due to the wide range of conditions and services this covers, all with very different care pathways. However, we are introducing the first ever waiting time standards for mental health services.</p><br /><p>These include an access and waiting time standard for Children and Young People with an Eating Disorder. This states that National Institute of Health and Care Excellence concordant treatment should commence within a maximum of four weeks from first contact with a designated healthcare professional for routine cases and within one week for urgent cases. In cases of emergency, the eating disorder service should be contacted to provide support within 24 hours. The ability of services to meet this standard will be monitored in 2016. From 2017, NHS England will set a minimum proportion of young people referred for assessment or treatment that are expected to receive treatment within the standardâs timeframe. Data collected in 2016 will help inform incremental percentage increases, with the aim of 95% of patients being treated within the standardâs timescale by 2020.</p><br /><p>We have also introduced an access and waiting times standard on Early Intervention in Psychosis announced in <em>Mental health services: achieving better access by 2020</em> which came into force in April 2015. Whilst focused on all ages, most individuals experiencing a first episode of psychosis are in the 16-25 age group.</p><br /><p>NHS England will be working with partner organisations to lead work on the development of further access and waiting time standards for childrenâs mental health as part of the transformation programme on children and young peopleâs mental health.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428813/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:44:05.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428813/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428813/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Mental Health Services: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made in preparation for the introduction of waiting time targets for child and adolescent mental health services; and when he plans for those waiting times to come into effect.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","16650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428814","Department of Health","false","2015-11-24","<p>Information prior to 2013/14 is not held centrally by the Department.</p><br /><p>Detailed below is an estimate of planned expenditure costs to Health Education England of providing training to student midwives since 2013/14.</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>New Students Commissioned</p></td><td><p>Planned Students in training</p></td><td><p>Estimate Cost (million)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2,563</p></td><td><p>6,874</p></td><td><p>Â£102.2m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2,603</p></td><td><p>6,624</p></td><td><p>Â£120.8m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2,617</p></td><td><p>7,058</p></td><td><p>Â£130.6m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: </em>multi professional education and training budget monitoring returns</p><br />","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428814/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:53:42.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428814/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428814/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Midwives: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the total cost was to his Department of training student midwives in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Maria Caulfield","Lewes","Maria Caulfield","16632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428815","Home Office","false","2016-01-04","<p>The below table provides details of immigration detainees detained at the end of June 2015 and is taken from quarterly published national statistics:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2015/detention</p><p><strong></strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>Held 28 Days or Fewer</p></td><td><p>Over 28 Days But Fewer Than Four Months</p></td><td><p>Four to Six Months</p></td><td><p>Six to Twelve Months</p></td><td><p>Over Twelve Months</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Foreign National Offenders</p></td><td><p>30% (263)</p></td><td><p>41% (365)</p></td><td><p>10% (84)</p></td><td><p>14% (123)</p></td><td><p>5% (49)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other Detainees</p></td><td><p>58% (1502)</p></td><td><p>35% (899)</p></td><td><p>4% (114)</p></td><td><p>2% (62)</p></td><td><p>1% (27)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>It is not possible to provide a break-down of foreign national offenders convicted of immigration offences and foreign national offenders convicted of non-immigration offences. Such data is not aggregated in national reporting systems, which would mean these questions could only be answered through a disproportionately expensive manual case search to collate the data.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428815/answer",,,,,,"2016-01-04T13:32:46.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428815/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428815/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428815/answer/previousversion/31130","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of immigration detainees who are (a) foreign national offenders convicted of immigration offences, (b) foreign national offenders convicted of non-immigration offences and (c) other detainees were held in immigration detention for (i) 28 days or fewer, (ii) over 28 days but fewer than four months and (iii) over four months in the last year.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","16675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428816","Home Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>At the end of June 2015, the proportion of people held in immigration detention who were foreign national offenders was 25% (884).</p><p>It is not possible to provide a break-down of foreign national offenders convicted of immigration offences and foreign national offenders convicted of non-immigration offences. Such data is not aggregated in national reporting systems, which would mean these questions could only be answered through a disproportionately expensive manual case search to collate the data.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428816/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:42:20.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428816/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428816/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428816/answer/previousversion/31133","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of people held in immigration detention are (a) foreign national offenders convicted of immigration related offences, (b) foreign national offenders convicted of other offences and (c) non-foreign nationals.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","16676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428817","Home Office","false","2015-11-20","<p>I refer the honourable member to my answer given to Parliamentary Question 15845 in response to a question tabled on 10 November by my honourable friend for Eastbourne.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428817/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T15:11:41.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428817/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428817/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428817/answer/previousversion/31139","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Home Office: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to embed the Family Test into its policy making.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","16710"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428818","Home Office","false","2015-11-26","<p>We do not discuss specific deployments of SIA officers. The Rt. Hon member can be confident that the Strategic Defence and Security Review is a good result for the whole of the UK.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428818/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T17:51:10.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428818/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428818/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Intelligence Services: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to her Statement of 16 November 2015, Official Report, columns 379 to 382, what proportion of the new security officers announced in that Statement she plans will be based in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","16634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428819","Home Office","false","2015-11-25","<p>Income from fees contributes to providing the resources necessary to fund delivery of, and improvements to the Border, Immigration and Citizenship system.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428819/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T15:48:35.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428819/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428819/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428819/answer/previousversion/31156","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Visas: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for what purposes her Department used the income it raised from visa applications in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Michelle Thomson","Edinburgh West","Michelle  Thomson","16686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428820","Home Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>The Home Office does not analyse the average amount people spend on visa applications before being granted entry to the UK. The Home Office provides a wide range of visa products and services and takes into account a range of factors when setting fees, so there is no typical fee amount.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428820/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:40:59.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428820/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428820/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428820/answer/previousversion/31157","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Visas: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the average amount people spent on visa applications before being granted entry to the UK in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Michelle Thomson","Edinburgh West","Michelle  Thomson","16687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428821","Home Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>This information is published in the Home Office Annual Report and Accounts 2014-15, a copy of which is available in the Vote Office.</p><p>Table 6.2 sets out an analysis of income from services provided to external and public sector customers.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428821/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T16:01:01.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428821/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428821/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428821/answer/previousversion/31148","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Visas: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for what reason her Department no longer publishes accounts of the revenue stream from visa services previously published by the UK Border Agency.","false","Biography information for Michelle Thomson","Edinburgh West","Michelle  Thomson","16684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428822","Home Office","false","2015-11-23","<p>We do not record income broken down for each category of visa.</p><p>However, the Home Office publishes the amount of income raised through fees charged for visa applications within the Home Officeâs Annual Report and Accounts for the three previous years, copies of which are available in the Vote Office.</p><p>Statistical information relating to volumes within each visa category are published on the Gov.uk website, and are available at the following link. https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2015/list-of-tables</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428822/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T17:17:17.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428822/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428822/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428822/answer/previousversion/31149","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Visas: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much revenue her Department has raised from each category of visa in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Michelle Thomson","Edinburgh West","Michelle  Thomson","16685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428823","Home Office","false","2015-12-02","<p>Home Office Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of international partners, as well as organisations and individuals in the public and private sectors, as part of the process of policy development and delivery. Details of these meetings are published on the Cabinet Office website on a quarterly basis.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428823/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-02T14:00:54.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428823/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428823/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","Counter-terrorism: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent discussions she has had with her Irish counterpart on steps to counter terrorist threats.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","16668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428824","Cabinet Office","false","2015-11-23","<p>As is the case with information relating to the proceedings of Cabinet and Cabinet Committees, detailed information about attendance at COBR meetings is not disclosed. As a general principle, where an emergency directly affects areas of competence of a Devolved Administration, then they will either be invited to attend or advised on significant developments.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428824/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T16:06:24.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428824/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428824/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-11-17","Cobra: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reason a representative of Northern Ireland was not present at the COBR meeting on 15 November 2015.","false","Biography information for Danny Kinahan","South Antrim","Danny Kinahan","16667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428825","Home Office","false","2015-11-20","<p>In respect of Kent police, the Home Office has recently received an application from the Kent Police and Crime Commissioner for Special Grant funding for the additional costs relating to Operation Stack. I will carefully consider the bid and make a decision in due course.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428825/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T15:24:12.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428825/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428825/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-17","M20: Road Traffic","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assistance the Government has given to (a) Kent Police, (b) Kent County Council, (c) other operational organisations and (d) businesses to cover costs incurred during the implementation of Operation Stack in Summer 2015.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","16665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428826","House of Commons Commission","false","2015-11-20","<p>We do not comment on matters of digital or physical security. I understand the Director of the Digital Service has discussed the matter with the hon. Member.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428826/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T12:39:33.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428826/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428826/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2015-11-17","Parliament: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, how many incidents of (a) hacking, (b) viruses and (c) data breaches were reported to the Parliamentary Digital Service in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","16688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428827","House of Commons Commission","false","2015-11-20","<p>We do not comment on matters of digital or physical security. I understand the Director of the Digital Service has discussed the matter with the hon. Member.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428827/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:51:01.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428827/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428827/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2015-11-17","Members' Constituency Work: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, what steps the Parliamentary Digital Service is taking to protect constituency casework data.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","16678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428828","House of Commons Commission","false","2015-11-20","<p>It is a long-standing practice that we do not comment in public on the security of Parliament. However, I can assure the hon. Member that arrangements are kept under continual review and those working on the Estate are advised of any changes. If he has particular concerns the Parliamentary Security Director and the Serjeant at Arms would be happy to meet with him.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428828/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T10:37:47.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428828/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428828/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2015-11-17","Parliament: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, if he will provide an update on whether there are plans for a review of security protocols for the Parliamentary Estate and what communication the Serjeant at Arms office has had with relevant government departments on increasing the security of the House and the safety of staff.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","16656"
