"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428922","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-11-30","<p>The Government has no plans to change any names of towns or cities in Northern Ireland, and would only do so with consensus. It remains fully committed to supporting the institutions and principles established under the Belfast Agreement and to affording due respect to the cultural traditions in Northern Ireland.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428922/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-30T12:19:12.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428922/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428922/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-11-17","Northern Ireland Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Dunlop on 29 October (HL2879) concerning the 1998 Belfast Agreement, whether the answer applies to changes in the names of cities and towns in Northern Ireland other than Londonderry.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL3645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428923","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-11-30","<p>The Government has held regular meetings with the Irish Government over the last two years in accordance with the established three-stranded approach.</p>",,"Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428923/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-30T12:18:52.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428923/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428923/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-11-17","Northern Ireland Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government on what dates in the last 24 months the government of the Republic of Ireland attended in any capacity meetings held under section 1 of the 1998 Belfast Agreement.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL3646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428924","Department for Education","false","2015-12-01","<p>We are currently considering the conclusions and recommendations of the caste feasibility study as part of our wider consideration of the implications of the <em>Tirkey v Chandok</em> tribunal judgments. We will keep the House informed of further developments on this matter.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428924/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-01T17:45:18.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428924/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428924/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-17","Castes: Discrimination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government whether they will publish the feasibility study of 2014 on caste discrimination.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL3647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428925","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-30","<p>I am grateful for Lord Moynihan's valuable contributions to that debate in the House.</p><p>The Minister for Sport has made it clear that a new approach to sport is needed. The Government published a consultation paper on a new sport strategy in early August and the responses received are being considered. The Government will publish its new strategy for sport in due course, the first such strategy for 13 years.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428925/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-30T12:25:56.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428925/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428925/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-17","Sports: Policy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, in the light of the debate in the House of Lords on 5 November (HL Deb, cols 1811â40) on the regeneration legacy of the London Olympic and Paralympic Games, what assessment they have made of Lord Moynihan's remarks that the UK should have a sports policy.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL3648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428926","Department of Health","false","2015-12-01","<p>The Government welcomes ukactiveâs report. It makes an important contribution to the debate on physical activity and builds on the framework for action set out by Public Health England last year in âEverybody Active Every Dayâ.</p><p><em></em></p><p>The Government recognises the health, economic and social benefits to individuals, communities and the nation of increasing physical activity levels. Since 2011, the Government has invested over Â£450 million in the PE and Sport Primary Premium in order to improve PE and sport. A further Â£46.5 million has been invested in School Games in order to provide all children, regardless of their ability, with a chance to participate in competitive sport. In addition Â£13 million has been invested in Change4life sports clubs which targets the least active children and helps them get more active.</p><br /><p>We are also committed to raising awareness among the public and health professionals of the benefits of physical activity. We have worked with experts to translate the Chief Medical Officersâ (CMOs) guidelines on physical activity into easy messages in the form of an infographic which health professionals can now use with their patients when they discuss physical activity. The UKâs CMOs have now asked the experts to carry out a similar piece of work on physical activity for children and young people. In addition, Public Health Englandâs Change4Life campaign continues to support families to make healthy choices, including being active.</p><p><em></em></p><p>Further action to increase physical activity and reduce sedentary behaviour will be taken via the Governmentâs new strategy for sport to be published shortly.</p><p><strong></strong></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428926/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-01T12:08:56.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428926/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428926/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","Exercise","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, in the light of a recent report by UKactive that lack of exercise is estimated to cause 37,000 deaths annually and cost the UK economy Â£20 billion a year, what steps they are taking to reduce levels of inactivity.","false","Biography information for Lord Pendry",,"Lord Pendry","HL3649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428927","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-01","<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) recognise that their customer service has not been good enough, and have taken major steps to improve, including recruiting 3,000 new staff into customer service roles, available outside normal office hours when many of their customers choose to call them. The process of recruiting and training the new staff is now complete. These improvements have started to make a difference. This month, HMRC have answered more than 80 per cent of calls, and average queue times are now around 10 minutes.</p><br /><p>HMRC also recognise that some customers have been waiting too long for a response to their complaint. HMRC have recovery plans in place and their performance is improving week on week.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428927/answer",,,,,"HL3651","2015-12-01T17:09:50.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428927/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428927/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-17","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, in the light of the press release by HMRC on 25 June, what initiatives HMRC have put in place to improve performance in respect of relieving public frustration at being able to make contact by telephone.","false","Biography information for Lord Quirk",,"Lord Quirk","HL3650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428928","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-01","<p>HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC) recognise that their customer service has not been good enough, and have taken major steps to improve, including recruiting 3,000 new staff into customer service roles, available outside normal office hours when many of their customers choose to call them. The process of recruiting and training the new staff is now complete. These improvements have started to make a difference. This month, HMRC have answered more than 80 per cent of calls, and average queue times are now around 10 minutes.</p><br /><p>HMRC also recognise that some customers have been waiting too long for a response to their complaint. HMRC have recovery plans in place and their performance is improving week on week.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428928/answer",,,,,"HL3650","2015-12-01T17:09:50.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428928/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428928/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-17","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord OâNeill of Gatley on 9 July (HL896, HL897) and 30 July (HL1654), why according to recent press reports HMRC are still failing to answer telephoned inquiries and complaints from the public within an acceptable time frame.","false","Biography information for Lord Quirk",,"Lord Quirk","HL3651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428929","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-01","<p>The North Atlantic Treaty Organisation is the cornerstone of our national security, and the ultimate guarantor of our defence. But the EU can play a useful complementary role, for example in missions in the Western Balkans and off the coast of Somalia. We always have, and always will, resist any proposal for an EU army.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428929/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-01T16:41:38.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428929/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428929/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-17","UK Membership of EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, in the light of the Prime Minister's recent assertions at the CBI Annual Conference on 9 November that the UK's security is provided through membership of the EU, what assessment they have made of the impact of NATO membership on the UK's security and whether they will continue to oppose any proposals for an EU army or other EU armed forces.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL3652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428930","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-30","<p>Local planning authorities can provide advice on whether consent is required for a notice in a specific location and decide whether such advertisements fall within any of the classes of advertisements that do not require express consent. General advice on advertisement consent is set out in national planning guidance on the GOV.UK website.</p><p>There is no requirement to include information about the ratio of UK contributions to the EU budget and the sums returned by way of grants to farmers and others.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428930/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-30T12:10:52.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428930/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428930/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-11-17","Agriculture: Subsidies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Gardiner of Kimble on 9 November (HL3057), whether they will now answer the additional questions asked about whether planning consent is required for farmers to erect notices advertising receipt of EU grants; and whether they will require all such advertising notices to include information about the ratio of UK contributions to the EU budget and the sums returned by way of grants to farmers and others.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL3653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428931","Department for Education","false","2015-12-01","<p>My earlier response to Lord Stoddartâs PQ HL 521 refers:</p><br /><p>âSchools are aware of their duties regarding impartiality and treatment of political issues. Sections 406 and 407 of the Education Act 1996 require maintained schools to prevent political indoctrination and secure the balanced treatment of political issues. This duty is reflected in the model funding agreement for academies and free schools.</p><br /><p>In Citizenship education, pupils are taught about local, regional and international governance and the United Kingdomâs relations with the rest of Europe, the Commonwealth, the United Nations and the wider world. Pupils will be equipped with the skills to think critically and debate political questions.â</p><br /><p>School governing bodies and academy trusts are responsible for considering if a member of staff has acted improperly in presenting their own views or beliefs to pupils.</p><br /><p>The Departmentâs â<em>Teacher Misconduct: the prohibition of teachersâ</em> advice is used by those involved in the teacher regulatory process, professional conduct panels and NCTL officials, to identify factors that should be taken into account when considering whether prohibition is appropriate. This advice makes clear that in considering the seriousness of a teacherâs behaviour it is important to consider the influential role that a teacher can play in the formation of pupilsâ views and behaviours. A teacherâs behaviour that is judged to promote extremist political or religious views or actions should be viewed very seriously in terms of its potential influence on children and young people and as a possible threat to the public interest, even if no criminal offence is involved.</p><br /><p>This advice can also be used to indicate to teachers the sorts of behaviour that could constitute serious misconduct, and so lead to prohibition and to help employers make a judgement on which cases should be referred to the NCTL.</p>",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428931/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-01T16:39:18.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428931/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428931/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-11-17","European Union: Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what action, if any, they plan to take to ensure that sections 406 and 407 of the Education Act 1996 are complied with between now and 2017 to ensure that lessons and discussions relating to the UK membership of the EU are balanced and impartial.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL3654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428932","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-25","<p>When the then Government first asked for expressions of interest in Final Investment Decisions (FID) enabling, EDF was the only nuclear developer to come forward, so it was appropriate to enter bilateral negotiations with EDF on this project. This Government continues to explore many different options for providing secure, affordable and clean electricity, making use of different technologies and commercial developers, including nuclear developers. The UK requires reliable, safe, base load electricity from new nuclear, and other low carbon generation sources, and price is one consideration amongst a number for achieving this.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428932/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T15:22:52.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428932/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428932/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-17","Hinkley Point C Power Station","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 3 November (HL3059) concerning the proposed Hinkley Point C nuclear power station project, what alternatives to the contract with EDF and China were explored, and with what results.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL3655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428933","Department of Health","false","2015-11-23","<p>This information is not collected by the Department. Health is a devolved matter across the four countries of the United Kingdom and the Department is only responsible for the health and care system in England.</p><br /><p>The ratio of National Health Service staff in England to the population of England is 0.019824. This is normally expressed as a ratio per 100,000 population, which in this case is 1,982.4 full-time equivalent staff per 100,000 population.</p><br /><p>The Department does not hold information on estimates of the number of health care staff in other countries.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428933/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T15:06:59.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428933/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428933/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-17","NHS: Staff","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majestyâs Government what is the ratio of NHS employees to the UK population; and how this compares with major European countries and the USA.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL3656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428934","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2015-11-25","<p>The table below shows the date of the count of, those eligible to vote in the by-election and the amount paid to Electoral Reform Services in respect of each by-election since the start of the 2014â15 session.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date of count</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Those eligible to vote </strong> <strong>in the by-election</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Amount paid to Electoral Reform Services</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>22 October 2014</p></td><td><p>All members of the House</p></td><td><p>Â£2,370</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>10 December 2014</p></td><td><p>Crossbench hereditary members</p></td><td><p>Â£950</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>3 February 2015</p></td><td><p>Crossbench hereditary members</p></td><td><p>Â£950</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>7 July 2015</p></td><td><p>Crossbench hereditary members</p></td><td><p>Â£950</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>16 September 2015</p></td><td><p>Conservative hereditary members</p></td><td><p>Â£950</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The by-election in October 2014 involved the manning of a polling station for a day.</p><p>Amounts are exclusive of VAT. The table does not include two recent by-elections in respect of which Electoral Reform Services has provided services but not yet been paid.</p>",,"Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428934/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-25T17:52:04.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428934/answer","Biography information for Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428934/answer",,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2015-11-17","Hereditary Peers: By-elections","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees how much has been paid to Electoral Reform Services for their supervision of each hereditary peers by-election since the start of the 2014â15 session in the House of Lords.","false","Biography information for Lord Trefgarne",,"Lord Trefgarne"