"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428307","Department of Health","false","2015-11-19","<p>NHS England does hold data on the individual reasons patients may have for seeking referral for a BRCA1/2 test. A new clinical commissioning policy to guide and expand access to BRCA testing was published by NHS England in July 2015. This policy is intended to provide greater clarity and equity for patients across England wishing to consider testing by providing consistent criteria for referral, where a referral is made by a specialist clinic.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428307/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-19T17:19:15.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428307/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428307/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-16","Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of information maintained by the NHS to enable his Department to assess the reasons why women choose to have a BRCA1/2 test.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","16389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428308","Department of Health","false","2015-11-19","<p>Data on molecular genetic testing for 2012-13 and subsequent years are not currently held centrally. The UK Genetic Testing Network (UKGTN) is working to publish data on molecular testing activity in collaboration with the Health and Social Care Information Centre (HSCIC) and NHS England. UKGTN is also working with the devolved administrations to ensure that they are legally able to share these data with the HSCIC.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428308/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-19T17:16:48.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428308/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428308/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-16","Genetics: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish data on molecular genetic test activity rates in 2012-13 and each subsequent year.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","16390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428309","Department of Health","false","2015-11-19","<p>NHS England published a new Clinical Commissioning Policy on Genetic Testing for BRCA1/2 mutations in July 2015, based on updated guidelines issued by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence. Subject to the need to appropriately handle patient identifiable data, NHS England would be willing to work with the UK Genetic Testing Network (UKGTN) to consider and monitor changes in uptake of BRCA testing following the publication of the 2015 Clinical Commissioning Policy.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428309/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-19T17:14:25.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428309/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428309/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-16","Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will require a UK Genetics Testing Network to audit Clinical Commissioning Policy: Genetic Testing for BRCA1/2 Mutations, published by NHS England in 2014.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","16391"
