"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428327","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-24","<p>The Department commissioned econometric research to estimate the labour market impact of Further Education (FE), which found that FE generates significant economic effects, resulting in sustained higher earnings and increased employment chances. This report was published in December 2014 and is available at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/further-education-comparing-labour-market-economic-benefits-from-qualifications-gained" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/further-education-comparing-labour-market-economic-benefits-from-qualifications-gained</a></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428327/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T11:41:27.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428327/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428327/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-16","Adult Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of adult education courses in helping people into work.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","16320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428329","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-08","<p>At Budget 2012, the Government announced it would move to taxing remote gambling on a place of consumption basis. This change came into force on 1<sup>st</sup> December 2014, and was expected to raise additional Exchequer revenues of Â£70 million in 2014-15, Â£240 million in 2015-16, and Â£270 million in 2016-17.</p><p>HMRC publish receipts from the three affected duties (general betting duty, pool betting duty and remote gaming duty). From April 2015, following the reforms, remote gaming duty receipts are published separately (they were previously combined with gaming duty). A breakdown of general betting duty and pools betting duty into remote and non-remote components is not available. The bulletin can be found here: <a href="https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutybulletins.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutybulletins.aspx</a>.</p><p>As the OBR mentioned in their November 2015 Economic and Fiscal Outlook, no yield from the reform was received until the beginning of 2015-16 because of an extension to the first accounting period.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428329/answer",,,,,,"2015-12-08T16:30:52.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428329/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428329/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-16","Gambling: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the tax revenue that may be received from the Point of Consumption Tax on online betting and gaming.","true","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","16373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428331","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-19","<p>The Government has committed to providing funding to help secure the National Wildlife Crime Unit until at least the end of March next year. Decisions on funding beyond March will be made as part of the current Spending Review process.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428331/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-19T12:41:49.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428331/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428331/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-11-16","National Wildlife Crime Unit: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans her Department has to renew its funding for the National Wildlife Crime Unit after March 2016.","false","Biography information for Gerald Jones","Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","Gerald Jones","16385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428332","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-23","<p>Since 2013 the Government has supported industry in delivering over 1.6 million measures which were installed in over 1.3 million households through the Energy Company Obligation (ECO) alone. We are now working with the industry and consumer groups on a new value-for-money approach.</p><br /><p>Weâve also commissioned an independent review led by Peter Bonfield to investigate quality, standards and consumer protection to ensure that the system properly supports and protects consumers.</p><br /><p>The National Infrastructure Commission will be resourced to carry out its task of advising Government on the UKâs infrastructure needs and priorities. It will not have adirectrole in funding infrastructure delivery.</p><br /><p>We are clear that support should be focussed on those with the greatest need.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428332/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-23T15:18:26.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428332/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428332/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428332/answer/previousversion/30997","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-16","Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps her Department is taking to improve the energy efficiency of homes; and whether any of the National Infrastructure Committee's funding will be available for use to increase home energy efficiency.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","16366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428333","Home Office","false","2015-11-20","<p>The allocations provided to forces were indicative and intended to inform the consultation process. No funding to West Midlands Police or any other force was affected by this error.</p><p>The Government is now minded to delay the implementation of new arrangements. Funding allocations for 2016/17 will be determined using existing arrangements and will be set out in the Provisional Police Grant Report in December. It is a matter for Police and Crime Commissioners, working with Chief Officers to determine how to best manage their available resources.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428333/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T14:40:42.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428333/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428333/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-16","Police: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of her Department's miscalculation of the amount of funding available for West Midlands Police on the adequacy of the provision of policing in Birmingham; and what steps she is taking to ensure effective policing in that city.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","16360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428335","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-19","<p>This Government recognises the value of science and innovation as a driver of economic success. We protected the science ring-fence over the last Parliament and are investing Â£6.9 billion in science capital from this year to 2021. There is clear and robust evidence of a link between R&amp;D investment and national productivity, including in OECD Economic Working Paper<em> 843 (2011): </em><a href="http://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/docserver/download/5kghwnhxwkhj.pdf?expires=1447868224&amp;id=id&amp;accname=guest&amp;checksum=FD50F59A6AFEEC34AE58B844317965CE" target="_blank">http://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/docserver/download/5kghwnhxwkhj.pdf?expires=1447868224&amp;id=id&amp;accname=guest&amp;checksum=FD50F59A6AFEEC34AE58B844317965CE</a></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428335/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-19T16:34:28.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428335/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428335/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-16","Science: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of increasing spending on the science capital commitment on UK productivity.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","16489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428336","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-19","<p>Younger workers tend to have less experience than older workers in the labour market, and so there is a risk that too high a wage rate may make them relatively less attractive to employers. So, to minimise any negative impact on employment of younger workers, the National Living Wage is limited to those 25 and over. The Government has not therefore made an estimate of what the fiscal impact of this policy change would be.</p><br /><p>The Office for Budgetary Responsibility estimate that, by 2020-21, the National Living Wage will increase income tax and NICs receipts by around Â£0.1bn, as set out in Table B.3 in of their July 2015 Economic and Fiscal Outlook. They assume that, by 2020-21, the overall impact of the policy on the public finances is to reduce public sector net borrowing by Â£0.2bn.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428336/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-19T15:38:10.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428336/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428336/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-16","Living Wage: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the increased tax revenue from extending the National Living Wage to those aged 18 to 25.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","16466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428338","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-20","<p>The Secretary of State and DCMS officials have discussed the Government's intention to implement a new broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) with industry representatives, and will be meeting fixed and mobile operators in coming weeks. The Government will launch a public consultation early next year in preparation for the implementation of a new broadband USO by 2020,with the ambition to give people the legal right to request a connection to broadband with speeds of 10 Mbps, no matter where in the country they live.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428338/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T12:15:20.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428338/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428338/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-16","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with industry representatives on the Universal Service Obligation announced by the Prime Minister on 7 November 2015; and what representations he has received from such representatives since.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","16478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428340","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-20","<p>DCMS has been discussing the Government's intention to implement a new broadband Universal Service Obligation (USO) with Ofcom, who will have a key role to play in providing technical and regulatory advice as the process moves forward. The Government will launch a public consultation early next year in preparation for the implementation of a new broadband USO by 2020,with the ambition to give people the legal right to request a connection to broadband with speeds of 10 Mbps, no matter where in the country they live.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428340/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-20T12:12:34.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428340/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428340/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-16","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Prime Minister's announcement of 7 November 2015 on broadband access, what discussions he has had with Ofcom on a Universal Service Obligation for broadband; and whether Ofcom were aware of the obligation before it was announced.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","16510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428341","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-26","<p>Government will be consulting in early 2016 on the Universal Service Obligation (USO) for broadband. The USO will be designed to be as efficient as possible, and ensure value for money for the consumer and taxpayer.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428341/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-26T17:19:27.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428341/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428341/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-16","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Prime Minister's announcement of 7 November 2015 on broadband access, what public funding has been assigned for the delivery of the Universal Service Obligation for broadband; and whether he plans to publish this information as part of the comprehensive spending review.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","16511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428342","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-19","<p>As announced by the Prime Minister on 7th November, the Government plans to launch the consultation in early 2016.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428342/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-19T15:24:48.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428342/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428342/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-16","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, with reference to the Prime Minister's announcement of 7 November 2015 on broadband access, whether the Government will consult on the Universal Service Obligation for broadband.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","16512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428344","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-19","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) discloses personal data from its registers to authorised third parties with a legitimate reason for requesting it. Data is only disclosed where it is fair and lawful to do so and in compliance with the Data Protection Act. Comprehensive safeguards are in place to ensure that DVLA data provided to third parties is requested for specific purposes and is used appropriately. Information on the organisations that the DVLA discloses data to can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/who-dvla-shares-data-with" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/who-dvla-shares-data-with</a></p><p>In 2014/15, the DVLA received Â£15.1m from data sharing activities. The DVLAâs data release charges are set to recover the cost of providing the information. While DVLA is permitted to charge a fee for the release of information under the reasonable cause provisions, it is not permitted to profit from it. The fees are set to recover the related administrative costs and so that it is the applicant and not the taxpayer who funds this activity.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428344/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-19T14:46:53.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428344/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428344/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-16","Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with whom did the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency share licence data in 2014-15; and what payments were received for such data sharing.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","16479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428347","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-18","<p>This is an operational matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government. The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428347/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-18T14:00:05.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428347/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428347/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-16","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff of the Financial Conduct Authority and the Financial Services Authority worked on money laundering enforcement in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","16376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428348","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-18","<p>This is an operational matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government. The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428348/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-18T14:01:51.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428348/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428348/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-16","Money Laundering: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, which companies were prosecuted by the Financial Conduct Authority or the Financial Services Authority for issues relating to money laundering in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","16375"
