"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428350","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-24","<p>Defra is currently carrying out a review of progress towards the targets for peat reduction in horticulture set out in the Natural Environment White Paper. Based on sales data from 2014, there has been a 24% reduction in peat sales for horticultural use in the UK since 2011.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428350/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-24T15:38:47.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428350/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428350/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-11-16","Peat Bogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress her Department has made towards the targets for protecting peat set out in the Natural Environment White Paper of 2011 since the publication of the last implementation update report in October 2014.","false","Biography information for Richard Benyon","Newbury","Richard Benyon","16344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428351","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-11-19","<p>The Government does not issue specific guidance to housing associations on the proportion of their new build properties that must be capable of adaption.</p><p>Local authorities are best placed to understand the housing needs in their area. National policy sets out clearly the need for local authorities to plan for the housing needs of all members of the community.</p><p>On 1 October, new optional Building Regulations came into force to make new homes more adaptable to peoples changing needs over time. Housing associations could choose to implement this, or any other adaptable housing standard, when setting standards for the new homes they build.</p><p>Separately through the Care and Support Specialised Housing fund the Government is providing up to Â£315 million to build over 4,000 specialised homes for older and disabled people.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428351/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-19T15:28:23.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428351/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428351/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-16","Housing: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department provides to housing associations on the proportion of their new build properties that must be capable of adaptation.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","16469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428352","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-19","<p>The government is committed to boosting productivity growth and narrowing the gap with other leading advanced economies. In July 2015 the government published âFixing the Foundations: Creating a more prosperous nationâ; a comprehensive plan that sets the agenda to reverse the UKâs long-term productivity problem.</p><br /><p>The financial services sector has a dual role in supporting UK productivity. As well as its own productivity performance, it is critical for supporting the rest of the economy, allocating resources and facilitating long term productive investment. In the latest remit letter to the Financial Policy Committee of the Bank of England, the Chancellor highlighted the importance of a stable financial system providing finance for productive investment.</p><br /><p>To promote the provision of finance to support productive investment, it is important that it can be measured accurately. The Bank of England, working with HM Treasury, have initiated research to create a better measurement of âfinance for productive investmentâ covering all asset classes and all stages of finance, with a view to publishing the data on a regular basis.</p><br />","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428352/answer",,,,,,"2015-11-19T16:48:39.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428352/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428352/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-16","Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that an approach supply of finance to productive investment is available to help increase productivity.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","16397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428353","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-20","<p>SQW Consultingâs UK Broadband impact study in 2013 estimates that the availability and take-up of faster broadband speeds will add about Â£17 billion to the UKâs annual Gross Value Added (GVA) by 2024.</p><p>This Government is helping increase productivity across the UK by investing in and widening access to key digital infrastructure. We are on track to deliver our commitment to provide superfast broadband coverage to 95% of the UK by the end of 2017.OurÂ£40m Broadband Connection Voucher Scheme was taken up by over 55,000 small and medium sized businesses - who employ a million people right across the UK and are already reporting, on average, a Â£1,300 per year increase in profits and a new job being created for every four new connections. ThePrime Minister recentlyannounced plans to ensure that every home and business can have access to fast broadband by the end of this Parliament.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428353/answer",,,,,"16396","2015-11-20T11:58:58.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428353/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428353/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-16","Broadband: Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the provision of high-speed broadband infrastructure on productivity.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","16395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428354","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-11-20","<p>SQW Consultingâs UK Broadband impact study in 2013 estimates that the availability and take-up of faster broadband speeds will add about Â£17 billion to the UKâs annual Gross Value Added (GVA) by 2024.</p><p>This Government is helping increase productivity across the UK by investing in and widening access to key digital infrastructure. We are on track to deliver our commitment to provide superfast broadband coverage to 95% of the UK by the end of 2017.OurÂ£40m Broadband Connection Voucher Scheme was taken up by over 55,000 small and medium sized businesses - who employ a million people right across the UK and are already reporting, on average, a Â£1,300 per year increase in profits and a new job being created for every four new connections. ThePrime Minister recentlyannounced plans to ensure that every home and business can have access to fast broadband by the end of this Parliament.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428354/answer",,,,,"16395","2015-11-20T11:58:59.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428354/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428354/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-11-16","Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to improve the UK's productivity.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","16396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428355","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-11-19","<p>The number of prisoners released on Home Detention Curfew (HDC) in England and Wales has fallen in recent years. This is principally due to the reduction in the number of prisoners eligible for the scheme.</p><br /><p>The Ministry of Justice only collates data on the number of prisoners released on HDC who are then recalled to prison for breach of their curfew conditions and this data is only available for England and Wales as a whole. It would incur disproportionate cost to isolate from this overall data those recalled prisoners who had been released on HDC from prisons in Devon.</p><br /><p>This data is published and can be located at the following link (table A3.5 details HDC recalls):</p><br /> <br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/424903/prison-releases-annual-2014.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/424903/prison-releases-annual-2014.xlsx</a></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428355/answer",,,,,"16340 ; 16341","2015-11-19T13:58:19.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428355/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428355/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-11-16","Prisoners' Release: Curfews","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for what reasons the number of prisoners being released on Home Detention Curfews in Devon decreased between 2011 and 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","16339"
